18¿é 12:5 "He who is at ease holds calamity in contempt, As prepared for those whose feet slip.
18¿é 12:6 "The tents of the destroyers prosper, And those who provoke God are secure, Whom God brings into their power.
18¿é 12:7 "But now ask the beasts, and let them teach you; And the birds of the heavens, and let them tell you.
18¿é 12:8 "Or speak to the earth, and let it teach you; And let the fish of the sea declare to you.
18¿é 12:9 "Who among all these does not know That the hand of the LORD has done this,
18¿é 12:10 In whose hand is the life of every living thing, And the breath of all mankind?
18¿é 12:11 "Does not the ear test words, As the palate tastes its food?
18¿é 12:12 "Wisdom is with aged men, [With] long life is understanding.
18¿é 12:13 "With Him are wisdom and might; To Him belong counsel and understanding.
18¿é 12:14 "Behold, He tears down, and it cannot be rebuilt; He imprisons a man, and there can be no release.
18¿é 12:15 "Behold, He restrains the waters, and they dry up; And He sends them out, and they inundate the earth.
18¿é 12:16 "With Him are strength and sound wisdom, The misled and the misleader belong to Him.
18¿é 12:17 "He makes counselors walk barefoot, And makes fools of judges.
18¿é 12:18 "He loosens the bond of kings, And binds their loins with a girdle.
18¿é 12:19 "He makes priests walk barefoot, And overthrows the secure ones.
18¿é 12:20 "He deprives the trusted ones of speech, And takes away the discernment of the elders.
18¿é 12:21 "He pours contempt on nobles, And loosens the belt of the strong.
18¿é 12:22 "He reveals mysteries from the darkness, And brings the deep darkness into light.
18¿é 12:23 "He makes the nations great, then destroys them; He enlarges the nations, then leads them away.
18¿é 12:24 "He deprives of intelligence the chiefs of the earth's people, And makes them wander in a pathless waste.
18¿é 12:25 "They grope in darkness with no light, And He makes them stagger like a drunken man.
18¿é 13:1 "Behold, my eye has seen all [this,] My ear has heard and understood it.
18¿é 13:2 "What you know I also know. I am not inferior to you.
18¿é 13:3 "But I would speak to the Almighty, And I desire to argue with God.
18¿é 13:4 "But you smear with lies; You are all worthless physicians.
18¿é 13:5 "O that you would be completely silent, And that it would become your wisdom!
18¿é 13:6 "Please hear my argument, And listen to the contentions of my lips.
18¿é 13:7 "Will you speak what is unjust for God, And speak what is deceitful for Him?
18¿é 13:8 "Will you show partiality for Him? Will you contend for God?
18¿é 13:9 "Will it be well when He examines you? Or will you deceive Him as one deceives a man?
18¿é 13:10 "He will surely reprove you, If you secretly show partiality.
18¿é 13:11 "Will not His majesty terrify you, And the dread of Him fall on you?
18¿é 13:12 "Your memorable sayings are proverbs of ashes, Your defenses are defenses of clay.
18¿é 13:13 "Be silent before me so that I may speak; Then let come on me what may.
18¿é 13:14 "Why should I take my flesh in my teeth, And put my life in my hands?
18¿é 13:15 "Though He slay me, I will hope in Him. Nevertheless I will argue my ways before Him.
18¿é 13:16 "This also will be my salvation, For a godless man may not come before His presence.
18¿é 13:17 "Listen carefully to my speech, And let my declaration [fill] your ears.
18¿é 13:18 "Behold now, I have prepared my case; I know that I will be vindicated.
18¿é 13:19 "Who will contend with me? For then I would be silent and die.
18¿é 13:20 "Only two things do not do to me, Then I will not hide from Thy face£º
18¿é 13:21 Remove Thy hand from me, And let not the dread of Thee terrify me.
18¿é 13:22 "Then call, and I will answer; Or let me speak, then reply to me.
18¿é 13:23 "How many are my iniquities and sins? Make known to me my rebellion and my sin.
18¿é 13:24 "Why dost Thou hide Thy face, And consider me Thine enemy?
18¿é 13:25 "Wilt Thou cause a driven leaf to tremble? Or wilt Thou pursue the dry chaff?
18¿é 13:26 "For Thou dost write bitter things against me, And dost make me to inherit the iniquities of my youth.
18¿é 13:27 "Thou dost put my feet in the stocks, And dost watch all my paths; Thou dost set a limit for the soles of my feet,
18¿é 13:28 While I am decaying like a rotten thing, Like a garment that is moth-eaten.
18¿é 14:1 "Man, who is born of woman, Is short-lived and full of turmoil.
18¿é 14:2 "Like a flower he comes forth and withers. He also flees like a shadow and does not remain.
18¿é 14:3 "Thou also dost open Thine eyes on him, And bring him into judgment with Thyself.
18¿é 14:4 "Who can make the clean out of the unclean? No one!
18¿é 14:5 "Since his days are determined, The number of his months is with Thee, And his limits Thou hast set so that he cannot pass.
18¿é 14:6 "Turn Thy gaze from him that he may rest, Until he fulfills his day like a hired man.
18¿é 14:7 "For there is hope for a tree, When it is cut down, that it will sprout again, And its shoots will not fail.
18¿é 14:8 "Though its roots grow old in the ground, And its stump dies in the dry soil,
18¿é 14:9 At the scent of water it will flourish And put forth sprigs like a plant.
18¿é 14:10 "But man dies and lies prostrate. Man expires, and where is he?
18¿é 14:11 "[As] water evaporates from the sea, And a river becomes parched and dried up,
18¿é 14:12 So man lies down and does not rise. Until the heavens be no more, He will not awake nor be aroused out of his sleep.
18¿é 14:13 "Oh that Thou wouldst hide me in Sheol, That Thou wouldst conceal me until Thy wrath returns [to Thee,] That Thou wouldst set a limit for me and remember me!
18¿é 14:14 "If a man dies, will he live [again?] All the days of my struggle I will wait, Until my change comes.
18¿é 14:15 "Thou wilt call, and I will answer Thee; Thou wilt long for the work of Thy hands.
18¿é 14:16 "For now Thou dost number my steps, Thou dost not observe my sin.
18¿é 14:17 "My transgression is sealed up in a bag, And Thou dost wrap up my iniquity.
18¿é 14:18 "But the falling mountain crumbles away, And the rock moves from its place;
18¿é 14:19 Water wears away stones, Its torrents wash away the dust of the earth; So Thou dost destroy man's hope.
18¿é 14:20 "Thou dost forever overpower him and he departs; [Thou] dost change his appearance and send him away.
18¿é 14:21 "His sons achieve honor, but he does not know [it;] Or they become insignificant, but he does not perceive it.
18¿é 14:22 "But his body pains him, And he mourns only for himself."
18¿é 15:1 Then Eliphaz the Temanite responded,
18¿é 15:2 "Should a wise man answer with windy knowledge, And fill himself with the east wind?
18¿é 15:3 "Should he argue with useless talk, Or with words which are not profitable?
18¿é 15:4 "Indeed, you do away with reverence, And hinder meditation before God.
18¿é 15:5 "For your guilt teaches your mouth, And you choose the language of the crafty.
18¿é 15:6 "Your own mouth condemns you, and not I; And your own lips testify against you.
18¿é 15:7 "Were you the first man to be born, Or were you brought forth before the hills?
18¿é 15:8 "Do you hear the secret counsel of God, And limit wisdom to yourself?
18¿é 15:9 "What do you know that we do not know? [What] do you understand that we do not?
18¿é 15:10 "Both the gray-haired and the aged are among us, Older than your father.
18¿é 15:11 "Are the consolations of God too small for you, Even the word [spoken] gently with you?
18¿é 15:12 "Why does your heart carry you away? And why do your eyes flash,
18¿é 15:13 That you should turn your spirit against God, And allow [such] words to go out of your mouth?
18¿é 15:14 "What is man, that he should be pure, Or he who is born of a woman, that he should be righteous?
18¿é 15:15 "Behold, He puts no trust in His holy ones, And the heavens are not pure in His sight;
18¿é 15:16 How much less one who is detestable and corrupt, Man, who drinks iniquity like water!
18¿é 15:17 "I will tell you, listen to me; And what I have seen I will also declare;
18¿é 15:18 What wise men have told, And have not concealed from their fathers,
18¿é 15:19 To whom alone the land was given, And no alien passed among them.
18¿é 15:20 "The wicked man writhes in pain all [his] days, And numbered are the years stored up for the ruthless.
18¿é 15:21 "Sounds of terror are in his ears, While at peace the destroyer comes upon him.
18¿é 15:22 "He does not believe that he will return from darkness, And he is destined for the sword.
18¿é 15:23 "He wanders about for food, saying, 'Where is it?' He knows that a day of darkness is at hand.
18¿é 15:24 "Distress and anguish terrify him, They overpower him like a king ready for the attack,
18¿é 15:25 Because he has stretched out his hand against God, And conducts himself arrogantly against the Almighty.
18¿é 15:26 "He rushes headlong at Him With his massive shield.
18¿é 15:27 "For he has covered his face with his fat, And made his thighs heavy with flesh.
18¿é 15:28 "And he has lived in desolate cities, In houses no one would inhabit, Which are destined to become ruins.
18¿é 15:29 "He will not become rich, nor will his wealth endure; And his grain will not bend down to the ground.
18¿é 15:30 "He will not escape from darkness; The flame will wither his shoots, And by the breath of His mouth he will go away.
18¿é 15:31 "Let him not trust in emptiness, deceiving himself; For emptiness will be his reward.
18¿é 15:32 "It will be accomplished before his time, And his palm branch will not be green.
18¿é 15:33 "He will drop off his unripe grape like the vine, And will cast off his flower like the olive tree.
18¿é 15:34 "For the company of the godless is barren, And fire consumes the tents of the corrupt.
18¿é 15:35 "They conceive mischief and bring forth iniquity, And their mind prepares deception."
18¿é 16:1 Then Job answered,
18¿é 16:2 "I have heard many such things; Sorry comforters are you all.
18¿é 16:3 "Is there [no] limit to windy words? Or what plagues you that you answer?
18¿é 16:4 "I too could speak like you, If I were in your place. I could compose words against you, And shake my head at you.
18¿é 16:5 "I could strengthen you with my mouth, And the solace of my lips could lessen [your pain.]
18¿é 16:6 "If I speak, my pain is not lessened, And if I hold back, what has left me?
18¿é 16:7 "But now He has exhausted me; Thou hast laid waste all my company.
18¿é 16:8 "And Thou hast shriveled me up, It has become a witness; And my leanness rises up against me, It testifies to my face.
18¿é 16:9 "His anger has torn me and hunted me down, He has gnashed at me with His teeth; My adversary glares at me.
18¿é 16:10 "They have gaped at me with their mouth, They have slapped me on the cheek with contempt; They have massed themselves against me.
18¿é 16:11 "God hands me over to ruffians, And tosses me into the hands of the wicked.
18¿é 16:12 "I was at ease, but He shattered me, And He has grasped me by the neck and shaken me to pieces; He has also set me up as His target.
18¿é 16:13 "His arrows surround me. Without mercy He splits my kidneys open; He pours out my gall on the ground.
18¿é 16:14 "He breaks through me with breach after breach; He runs at me like a warrior.
18¿é 16:15 "I have sewed sackcloth over my skin, And thrust my horn in the dust.
18¿é 16:16 "My face is flushed from weeping, And deep darkness is on my eyelids,
18¿é 16:17 Although there is no violence in my hands, And my prayer is pure.
18¿é 16:18 "O earth, do not cover my blood, And let there be no [resting] place for my cry.
18¿é 16:19 "Even now, behold, my witness is in heaven, And my advocate is on high.
18¿é 16:20 "My friends are my scoffers; My eye weeps to God.
18¿é 16:21 "O that a man might plead with God As a man with his neighbor!
18¿é 16:22 "For when a few years are past, I shall go the way of no return.
18¿é 17:1 "My spirit is broken, my days are extinguished, The grave is [ready] for me.
18¿é 17:2 "Surely mockers are with me, And my eye gazes on their provocation.
18¿é 17:3 "Lay down, now, a pledge for me with Thyself; Who is there that will be my guarantor?
18¿é 17:4 "For Thou hast kept their heart from understanding; Therefore Thou wilt not exalt [them.]
18¿é 17:5 "He who informs against friends for a share [of the spoil,] The eyes of his children also shall languish.
18¿é 17:6 "But He has made me a byword of the people, And I am one at whom men spit.
18¿é 17:7 "My eye has also grown dim because of grief, And all my members are as a shadow.
18¿é 17:8 "The upright shall be appalled at this, And the innocent shall stir up himself against the godless.
18¿é 17:9 "Nevertheless the righteous shall hold to his way, And he who has clean hands shall grow stronger and stronger.
18¿é 17:10 "But come again all of you now, For I do not find a wise man among you.
18¿é 17:11 "My days are past, my plans are torn apart, [Even] the wishes of my heart.
18¿é 17:12 "They make night into day, [saying,] 'The light is near,' in the presence of darkness.
18¿é 17:13 "If I look for Sheol as my home, I make my bed in the darkness;
18¿é 17:14 If I call to the pit, 'You are my father'; To the worm, 'my mother and my sister';
18¿é 17:15 Where now is my hope? And who regards my hope?
18¿é 17:16 "Will it go down with me to Sheol? Shall we together go down into the dust?"
18¿é 18:1 Then Bildad the Shuhite responded,
18¿é 18:2 "How long will you hunt for words? Show understanding and then we can talk.
18¿é 18:3 "Why are we regarded as beasts, As stupid in your eyes?
18¿é 18:4 "O you who tear yourself in your anger-- For your sake is the earth to be abandoned, Or the rock to be moved from its place?
18¿é 18:5 "Indeed, the light of the wicked goes out, And the flame of his fire gives no light.
18¿é 18:6 "The light in his tent is darkened, And his lamp goes out above him.
18¿é 18:7 "His vigorous stride is shortened, And his own scheme brings him down.
18¿é 18:8 "For he is thrown into the net by his own feet, And he steps on the webbing.
18¿é 18:9 "A snare seizes [him] by the heel, [And] a trap snaps shut on him.
18¿é 18:10 "A noose for him is hidden in the ground, And a trap for him on the path.
18¿é 18:11 "All around terrors frighten him, And harry him at every step.
18¿é 18:12 "His strength is famished, And calamity is ready at his side.
18¿é 18:13 "His skin is devoured by disease, The first-born of death devours his limbs.
18¿é 18:14 "He is torn from the security of his tent, And they march him before the king of terrors.
18¿é 18:15 "There dwells in his tent nothing of his; Brimstone is scattered on his habitation.
18¿é 18:16 "His roots are dried below, And his branch is cut off above.
18¿é 18:17 "Memory of him perishes from the earth, And he has no name abroad.
18¿é 18:18 "He is driven from light into darkness, And chased from the inhabited world.
18¿é 18:19 "He has no offspring or posterity among his people, Nor any survivor where he sojourned.
18¿é 18:20 "Those in the west are appalled at his fate, And those in the east are seized with horror.
18¿é 18:21 "Surely such are the dwellings of the wicked, And this is the place of him who does not know God."
18¿é 19:1 Then Job responded,
18¿é 19:2 "How long will you torment me, And crush me with words?
18¿é 19:3 "These ten times you have insulted me, You are not ashamed to wrong me.
18¿é 19:4 "Even if I have truly erred, My error lodges with me.
18¿é 19:5 "If indeed you vaunt yourselves against me, And prove my disgrace to me,
18¿é 19:6 Know then that God has wronged me, And has closed His net around me.
18¿é 19:7 "Behold, I cry, 'Violence!' but I get no answer; I shout for help, but there is no justice.
18¿é 19:8 "He has walled up my way so that I cannot pass; And He has put darkness on my paths.
18¿é 19:9 "He has stripped my honor from me, And removed the crown from my head.
18¿é 19:10 "He breaks me down on every side, and I am gone; And He has uprooted my hope like a tree.
18¿é 19:11 "He has also kindled His anger against me, And considered me as His enemy.
18¿é 19:12 "His troops come together, And build up their way against me, And camp around my tent.
18¿é 19:13 "He has removed my brothers far from me, And my acquaintances are completely estranged from me.
18¿é 19:14 "My relatives have failed, And my intimate friends have forgotten me.
18¿é 19:15 "Those who live in my house and my maids consider me a stranger. I am a foreigner in their sight.
18¿é 19:16 "I call to my servant, but he does not answer, I have to implore him with my mouth.
18¿é 19:17 "My breath is offensive to my wife, And I am loathsome to my own brothers.
18¿é 19:18 "Even young children despise me; I rise up and they speak against me.
18¿é 19:19 "All my associates abhor me, And those I love have turned against me.
18¿é 19:20 "My bone clings to my skin and my flesh, And I have escaped [only] by the skin of my teeth.
18¿é 19:21 "Pity me, pity me, O you my friends, For the hand of God has struck me.
18¿é 19:22 "Why do you persecute me as God [does,] And are not satisfied with my flesh?
18¿é 19:23 "Oh that my words were written! Oh that they were inscribed in a book!
18¿é 19:24 "That with an iron stylus and lead They were engraved in the rock forever!
18¿é 19:25 "And as for me, I know that my Redeemer lives, And at the last He will take His stand on the earth.
18¿é 19:26 "Even after my skin is destroyed, Yet from my flesh I shall see God;
18¿é 19:27 Whom I myself shall behold, And whom my eyes shall see and not another. My heart faints within me.
18¿é 19:28 "If you say, 'How shall we persecute him?' And 'What pretext for a case against him can we find?'
18¿é 19:29 "[Then] be afraid of the sword for yourselves, For wrath [brings] the punishment of the sword, So that you may know there is judgment."
18¿é 20:1 Then Zophar the Naamathite answered,
18¿é 20:2 "Therefore my disquieting thoughts make me respond, Even because of my inward agitation.
18¿é 20:3 "I listened to the reproof which insults me, And the spirit of my understanding makes me answer.
18¿é 20:4 "Do you know this from of old, From the establishment of man on earth,
18¿é 20:5 That the triumphing of the wicked is short, And the joy of the godless momentary?
18¿é 20:6 "Though his loftiness reaches the heavens, And his head touches the clouds,
18¿é 20:7 He perishes forever like his refuse; Those who have seen him will say, 'Where is he?'
18¿é 20:8 "He flies away like a dream, and they cannot find him; Even like a vision of the night he is chased away.
18¿é 20:9 "The eye which saw him sees him no more, And his place no longer beholds him.
18¿é 20:10 "His sons favor the poor, And his hands give back his wealth.
18¿é 20:11 "His bones are full of his youthful vigor, But it lies down with him in the dust.
18¿é 20:12 "Though evil is sweet in his mouth, [And] he hides it under his tongue,
18¿é 20:13 [Though] he desires it and will not let it go, But holds it in his mouth,
18¿é 20:14 [Yet] his food in his stomach is changed To the venom of cobras within him.
18¿é 20:15 "He swallows riches, But will vomit them up; God will expel them from his belly.
18¿é 20:16 "He sucks the poison of cobras; The viper's tongue slays him.
18¿é 20:17 "He does not look at the streams, The rivers flowing with honey and curds.
18¿é 20:18 "He returns what he has attained And cannot swallow [it;] As to the riches of his trading, He cannot even enjoy [them.]
18¿é 20:19 "For he has oppressed [and] forsaken the poor; He has seized a house which he has not built.
18¿é 20:20 "Because he knew no quiet within him He does not retain anything he desires.
18¿é 20:21 "Nothing remains for him to devour, Therefore his prosperity does not endure.
18¿é 20:22 "In the fulness of his plenty he will be cramped; The hand of everyone who suffers will come [against] him.
18¿é 20:23 "When he fills his belly, [God] will send His fierce anger on him And will rain [it] on him while he is eating.
18¿é 20:24 "He may flee from the iron weapon, [But] the bronze bow will pierce him.
18¿é 20:25 "It is drawn forth and comes out of his back, Even the glittering point from his gall. Terrors come upon him,
18¿é 20:26 Complete darkness is held in reserve for his treasures, And unfanned fire will devour him; It will consume the survivor in his tent.
18¿é 20:27 "The heavens will reveal his iniquity, And the earth will rise up against him.
18¿é 20:28 "The increase of his house will depart; [His possessions] will flow away in the day of His anger.
18¿é 20:29 "This is the wicked man's portion from God, Even the heritage decreed to him by God."
18¿é 21:1 Then Job answered,
18¿é 21:2 "Listen carefully to my speech, And let this be your [way of] consolation.
18¿é 21:3 "Bear with me that I may speak; Then after I have spoken, you may mock.
18¿é 21:4 "As for me, is my complaint to man? And why should I not be impatient?
18¿é 21:5 "Look at me, and be astonished, And put [your] hand over [your] mouth.
18¿é 21:6 "Even when I remember, I am disturbed, And horror takes hold of my flesh.
18¿é 21:7 "Why do the wicked [still] live, Continue on, also become very powerful?
18¿é 21:8 "Their descendants are established with them in their sight, And their offspring before their eyes,
18¿é 21:9 Their houses are safe from fear, Neither is the rod of God on them.
18¿é 21:10 "His ox mates without fail; His cow calves and does not abort.
18¿é 21:11 "They send forth their little ones like the flock, And their children skip about.
18¿é 21:12 "They sing to the timbrel and harp And rejoice at the sound of the flute.
18¿é 21:13 "They spend their days in prosperity, And suddenly they go down to Sheol.
18¿é 21:14 "And they say to God, 'Depart from us! We do not even desire the knowledge of Thy ways.
18¿é 21:15 'Who is the Almighty, that we should serve Him, And what would we gain if we entreat Him?'
18¿é 21:16 "Behold, their prosperity is not in their hand; The counsel of the wicked is far from me.
18¿é 21:17 "How often is the lamp of the wicked put out, Or [does] their calamity fall on them? Does God apportion destruction in His anger?
18¿é 21:18 "Are they as straw before the wind, And like chaff which the storm carries away?
18¿é 21:19 "[You say,] 'God stores away a man's iniquity for his sons.' Let God repay him so that he may know [it.]
18¿é 21:20 "Let his own eyes see his decay, And let him drink of the wrath of the Almighty.
18¿é 21:21 "For what does he care for his household after him, When the number of his months is cut off?
18¿é 21:22 "Can anyone teach God knowledge, In that He judges those on high?
18¿é 21:23 "One dies in his full strength, Being wholly at ease and satisfied;
18¿é 21:24 His sides are filled out with fat, And the marrow of his bones is moist,
18¿é 21:25 While another dies with a bitter soul, Never even tasting [anything] good.
18¿é 21:26 "Together they lie down in the dust, And worms cover them.
18¿é 21:27 "Behold, I know your thoughts, And the plans by which you would wrong me.
18¿é 21:28 "For you say, 'Where is the house of the nobleman, And where is the tent, the dwelling places of the wicked?'
18¿é 21:29 "Have you not asked wayfaring men, And do you not recognize their witness?
18¿é 21:30 "For the wicked is reserved for the day of calamity; They will be led forth at the day of fury.
18¿é 21:31 "Who will confront him with his actions, And who will repay him for what he has done?
18¿é 21:32 "While he is carried to the grave, [Men] will keep watch over [his] tomb.
18¿é 21:33 "The clods of the valley will gently cover him; Moreover, all men will follow after him, While countless ones [go] before him.
18¿é 21:34 "How then will you vainly comfort me, For your answers remain [full of] falsehood?"
18¿é 22:1 Then Eliphaz the Temanite responded,
18¿é 22:2 "Can a vigorous man be of use to God, Or a wise man be useful to himself?
18¿é 22:3 "Is there any pleasure to the Almighty if you are righteous, Or profit if you make your ways perfect?
18¿é 22:4 "Is it because of your reverence that He reproves you, That He enters into judgment against you?
18¿é 22:5 "Is not your wickedness great, And your iniquities without end?
18¿é 22:6 "For you have taken pledges of your brothers without cause, And stripped men naked.
18¿é 22:7 "To the weary you have given no water to drink, And from the hungry you have withheld bread.
18¿é 22:8 "But the earth belongs to the mighty man, And the honorable man dwells in it.
18¿é 22:9 "You have sent widows away empty, And the strength of the orphans has been crushed.
18¿é 22:10 "Therefore snares surround you, And sudden dread terrifies you,
18¿é 22:11 Or darkness, so that you cannot see, And an abundance of water covers you.
18¿é 22:12 "Is not God [in] the height of heaven? Look also at the distant stars, how high they are!
18¿é 22:13 "And you say, 'What does God know? Can He judge through the thick darkness?
18¿é 22:14 'Clouds are a hiding place for Him, so that He cannot see; And He walks on the vault of heaven.'
18¿é 22:15 "Will you keep to the ancient path Which wicked men have trod,
18¿é 22:16 Who were snatched away before their time, Whose foundations were washed away by a river?
18¿é 22:17 "They said to God, 'Depart from us!' And 'What can the Almighty do to them?'
18¿é 22:18 "Yet He filled their houses with good [things;] But the counsel of the wicked is far from me.
18¿é 22:19 "The righteous see and are glad, And the innocent mock them,
18¿é 22:20 [Saying,] 'Truly our adversaries are cut off, And their abundance the fire has consumed.'
18¿é 22:21 "Yield now and be at peace with Him; Thereby good will come to you.
18¿é 22:22 "Please receive instruction from His mouth, And establish His words in your heart.
18¿é 22:23 "If you return to the Almighty, you will be restored; If you remove unrighteousness far from your tent,
18¿é 22:24 And place [your] gold in the dust, And [the gold of] Ophir among the stones of the brooks,
18¿é 22:25 Then the Almighty will be your gold And choice silver to you.
18¿é 22:26 "For then you will delight in the Almighty, And lift up your face to God.
18¿é 22:27 "You will pray to Him, and He will hear you; And you will pay your vows.
18¿é 22:28 "You will also decree a thing, and it will be established for you; And light will shine on your ways.
18¿é 22:29 "When you are cast down, you will speak with confidence And the humble person He will save.
18¿é 22:30 "He will deliver one who is not innocent, And he will be delivered through the cleanness of your hands."
18¿é 23:1 Then Job replied,
18¿é 23:2 "Even today my complaint is rebellion; His hand is heavy despite my groaning.
18¿é 23:3 "Oh that I knew where I might find Him, That I might come to His seat!
18¿é 23:4 "I would present [my] case before Him And fill my mouth with arguments.
18¿é 23:5 "I would learn the words [which] He would answer, And perceive what He would say to me.
18¿é 23:6 "Would He contend with me by the greatness of [His] power? No, surely He would pay attention to me.
18¿é 23:7 "There the upright would reason with Him; And I would be delivered forever from my Judge.
18¿é 23:8 "Behold, I go forward but He is not [there,] And backward, but I cannot perceive Him;
18¿é 23:9 When He acts on the left, I cannot behold [Him;] He turns on the right, I cannot see Him.
18¿é 23:10 "But He knows the way I take; [When] He has tried me, I shall come forth as gold.
18¿é 23:11 "My foot has held fast to His path; I have kept His way and not turned aside.
18¿é 23:12 "I have not departed from the command of His lips; I have treasured the words of His mouth more than my necessary food.
18¿é 23:13 "But He is unique and who can turn Him? And [what] His soul desires, that He does.
18¿é 23:14 "For He performs what is appointed for me, And many such [decrees] are with Him.
18¿é 23:15 "Therefore, I would be dismayed at His presence; [When] I consider, I am terrified of Him.
18¿é 23:16 "[It is] God [who] has made my heart faint, And the Almighty [who] has dismayed me,
18¿é 23:17 But I am not silenced by the darkness, Nor deep gloom [which] covers [me.]
18¿é 24:1 "Why are times not stored up by the Almighty, And why do those who know Him not see His days?
18¿é 24:2 "Some remove the landmarks; They seize and devour flocks.
18¿é 24:3 "They drive away the donkeys of the orphans; They take the widow's ox for a pledge.
18¿é 24:4 "They push the needy aside from the road; The poor of the land are made to hide themselves altogether.
18¿é 24:5 "Behold, as wild donkeys in the wilderness They go forth seeking food in their activity, As bread for [their] children in the desert.
18¿é 24:6 "They harvest their fodder in the field, And they glean the vineyard of the wicked.
18¿é 24:7 "They spend the night naked, without clothing, And have no covering against the cold.
18¿é 24:8 "They are wet with the mountain rains, And they hug the rock for want of a shelter.
18¿é 24:9 "Others snatch the orphan from the breast, And against the poor they take a pledge.
18¿é 24:10 "They cause [the poor] to go about naked without clothing, And they take away the sheaves from the hungry.
18¿é 24:11 "Within the walls they produce oil; They tread wine presses but thirst.
18¿é 24:12 "From the city men groan, And the souls of the wounded cry out; Yet God does not pay attention to folly.
18¿é 24:13 "Others have been with those who rebel against the light; They do not want to know its ways, Nor abide in its paths.
18¿é 24:14 "The murderer arises at dawn; He kills the poor and the needy, And at night he is as a thief.
18¿é 24:15 "And the eye of the adulterer waits for the twilight, Saying, 'No eye will see me.' And he disguises his face.
18¿é 24:16 "In the dark they dig into houses, They shut themselves up by day; They do not know the light.
18¿é 24:17 "For the morning is the same to him as thick darkness, For he is familiar with the terrors of thick darkness.
18¿é 24:18 "They are insignificant on the surface of the water; Their portion is cursed on the earth. They do not turn toward the vineyards.
18¿é 24:19 "Drought and heat consume the snow waters, [So does] Sheol [those who] have sinned.
18¿é 24:20 "A mother will forget him; The worm feeds sweetly till he is remembered no more. And wickedness will be broken like a tree.
18¿é 24:21 "He wrongs the barren woman, And does no good for the widow.
18¿é 24:22 "But He drags off the valiant by His power; He rises, but no one has assurance of life.
18¿é 24:23 "He provides them with security, and they are supported; And His eyes are on their ways.
18¿é 24:24 "They are exalted a little while, then they are gone; Moreover, they are brought low and like everything gathered up; Even like the heads of grain they are cut off.
18¿é 24:25 "Now if it is not so, who can prove me a liar, And make my speech worthless?"
18¿é 25:1 Then Bildad the Shuhite answered,
18¿é 25:2 "Dominion and awe belong to Him Who establishes peace in His heights.
18¿é 25:3 "Is there any number to His troops? And upon whom does His light not rise?
18¿é 25:4 "How then can a man be just with God? Or how can he be clean who is born of woman?
18¿é 25:5 "If even the moon has no brightness And the stars are not pure in His sight,
18¿é 25:6 How much less man, [that] maggot, And the son of man, [that] worm! "
18¿é 26:1 Then Job responded,
18¿é 26:2 "What a help you are to the weak! How you have saved the arm without strength!
18¿é 26:3 "What counsel you have given to [one] without wisdom! What helpful insight you have abundantly provided!
18¿é 26:4 "To whom have you uttered words? And whose spirit was expressed through you?
18¿é 26:5 "The departed spirits tremble Under the waters and their inhabitants.
18¿é 26:6 "Naked is Sheol before Him And Abaddon has no covering.
18¿é 26:7 "He stretches out the north over empty space, And hangs the earth on nothing.
18¿é 26:8 "He wraps up the waters in His clouds; And the cloud does not burst under them.
18¿é 26:9 "He obscures the face of the full moon, And spreads His cloud over it.
18¿é 26:10 "He has inscribed a circle on the surface of the waters, At the boundary of light and darkness.
18¿é 26:11 "The pillars of heaven tremble, And are amazed at His rebuke.
18¿é 26:12 "He quieted the sea with His power, And by His understanding He shattered Rahab.
18¿é 26:13 "By His breath the heavens are cleared; His hand has pierced the fleeing serpent.
18¿é 26:14 "Behold, these are the fringes of His ways; And how faint a word we hear of Him! But His mighty thunder, who can understand?"
18¿é 27:1 Then Job continued his discourse and said,
18¿é 27:2 "As God lives, who has taken away my right, And the Almighty, who has embittered my soul,
18¿é 27:3 For as long as life is in me, And the breath of God is in my nostrils,
18¿é 27:4 My lips certainly will not speak unjustly, Nor will my tongue mutter deceit.
18¿é 27:5 "Far be it from me that I should declare you right; Till I die I will not put away my integrity from me.
18¿é 27:6 "I hold fast my righteousness and will not let it go. My heart does not reproach any of my days.
18¿é 27:7 "May my enemy be as the wicked, And my opponent as the unjust.
18¿é 27:8 "For what is the hope of the godless when he is cut off, When God requires his life?
18¿é 27:9 "Will God hear his cry, When distress comes upon him?
18¿é 27:10 "Will he take delight in the Almighty, Will he call on God at all times?
18¿é 27:11 "I will instruct you in the power of God; What is with the Almighty I will not conceal.
18¿é 27:12 "Behold, all of you have seen [it;] Why then do you act foolishly?
18¿é 27:13 "This is the portion of a wicked man from God, And the inheritance [which] tyrants receive from the Almighty.
18¿é 27:14 "Though his sons are many, they are destined for the sword; And his descendants will not be satisfied with bread.
18¿é 27:15 "His survivors will be buried because of the plague, And their widows will not be able to weep.
18¿é 27:16 "Though he piles up silver like dust, And prepares garments as [plentiful as] the clay;
18¿é 27:17 He may prepare [it,] but the just will wear [it,] And the innocent will divide the silver.
18¿é 27:18 "He has built his house like the spider's web, Or as a hut [which] the watchman has made.
18¿é 27:19 "He lies down rich, but never again; He opens his eyes, and it is no more.
18¿é 27:20 "Terrors overtake him like a flood; A tempest steals him away in the night.
18¿é 27:21 "The east wind carries him away, and he is gone, For it whirls him away from his place.
18¿é 27:22 "For it will hurl at him without sparing; He will surely try to flee from its power.
18¿é 27:23 "[Men] will clap their hands at him, And will hiss him from his place.
18¿é 28:1 "Surely there is a mine for silver, And a place where they refine gold.
18¿é 28:2 "Iron is taken from the dust, And from rock copper is smelted.
18¿é 28:3 "[Man] puts an end to darkness, And to the farthest limit he searches out The rock in gloom and deep shadow.
18¿é 28:4 "He sinks a shaft far from habitation, Forgotten by the foot; They hang and swing to and fro far from men.
18¿é 28:5 "The earth, from it comes food, And underneath it is turned up as fire.
18¿é 28:6 "Its rocks are the source of sapphires, And its dust [contains] gold.
18¿é 28:7 "The path no bird of prey knows, Nor has the falcon's eye caught sight of it.
18¿é 28:8 "The proud beasts have not trodden it, Nor has the [fierce] lion passed over it.
18¿é 28:9 "He puts his hand on the flint; He overturns the mountains at the base.
18¿é 28:10 "He hews out channels through the rocks; And his eye sees anything precious.
18¿é 28:11 "He dams up the streams from flowing; And what is hidden he brings out to the light.
18¿é 28:12 "But where can wisdom be found? And where is the place of understanding?
18¿é 28:13 "Man does not know its value, Nor is it found in the land of the living.
18¿é 28:14 "The deep says, 'It is not in me'; And the sea says, 'It is not with me.'
18¿é 28:15 "Pure gold cannot be given in exchange for it, Nor can silver be weighed as its price.
18¿é 28:16 "It cannot be valued in the gold of Ophir, In precious onyx, or sapphire.
18¿é 28:17 "Gold or glass cannot equal it, Nor can it be exchanged for articles of fine gold.
18¿é 28:18 "Coral and crystal are not to be mentioned; And the acquisition of wisdom is above [that of] pearls.
18¿é 28:19 "The topaz of Ethiopia cannot equal it, Nor can it be valued in pure gold.
18¿é 28:20 "Where then does wisdom come from? And where is the place of understanding?
18¿é 28:21 "Thus it is hidden from the eyes of all living, And concealed from the birds of the sky.
18¿é 28:22 "Abaddon and Death say, 'With our ears we have heard a report of it.'
18¿é 28:23 "God understands its way; And He knows its place.
18¿é 28:24 "For He looks to the ends of the earth, And sees everything under the heavens.
18¿é 28:25 "When He imparted weight to the wind, And meted out the waters by measure,
18¿é 28:26 When He set a limit for the rain, And a course for the thunderbolt,
18¿é 28:27 Then He saw it and declared it; He established it and also searched it out.
18¿é 28:28 "And to man He said, 'Behold, the fear of the Lord, that is wisdom; And to depart from evil is understanding.'"
18¿é 29:1 And Job again took up his discourse and said,
18¿é 29:2 "Oh that I were as in months gone by, As in the days when God watched over me;
18¿é 29:3 When His lamp shone over my head, [And] by His light I walked through darkness;
18¿é 29:4 As I was in the prime of my days, When the friendship of God [was] over my tent;
18¿é 29:5 When the Almighty was yet with me, [And] my children were around me;
18¿é 29:6 When my steps were bathed in butter, And the rock poured out for me streams of oil!
18¿é 29:7 "When I went out to the gate of the city, When I took my seat in the square;
18¿é 29:8 The young men saw me and hid themselves, And the old men arose [and] stood.
18¿é 29:9 "The princes stopped talking, And put [their] hands on their mouths;
18¿é 29:10 The voice of the nobles was hushed, And their tongue stuck to their palate.
18¿é 29:11 "For when the ear heard, it called me blessed; And when the eye saw, it gave witness of me,
18¿é 29:12 Because I delivered the poor who cried for help, And the orphan who had no helper.
18¿é 29:13 "The blessing of the one ready to perish came upon me, And I made the widow's heart sing for joy.
18¿é 29:14 "I put on righteousness, and it clothed me; My justice was like a robe and a turban.
18¿é 29:15 "I was eyes to the blind, And feet to the lame.
18¿é 29:16 "I was a father to the needy, And I investigated the case which I did not know.
18¿é 29:17 "And I broke the jaws of the wicked, And snatched the prey from his teeth.
18¿é 29:18 "Then I thought, 'I shall die in my nest, And I shall multiply [my] days as the sand.
18¿é 29:19 'My root is spread out to the waters, And dew lies all night on my branch.
18¿é 29:20 'My glory is [ever] new with me, And my bow is renewed in my hand.'
18¿é 29:21 "To me they listened and waited, And kept silent for my counsel.
18¿é 29:22 "After my words they did not speak again, And my speech dropped on them.
18¿é 29:23 "And they waited for me as for the rain, And opened their mouth as for the spring rain.
18¿é 29:24 "I smiled on them when they did not believe, And the light of my face they did not cast down.
18¿é 29:25 "I chose a way for them and sat as chief, And dwelt as a king among the troops, As one who comforted the mourners.
18¿é 30:1 "But now those younger than I mock me, Whose fathers I disdained to put with the dogs of my flock.
18¿é 30:2 "Indeed, what [good was] the strength of their hands to me? Vigor had perished from them.
18¿é 30:3 "From want and famine they are gaunt Who gnaw the dry ground by night in waste and desolation,
18¿é 30:4 Who pluck mallow by the bushes, And whose food is the root of the broom shrub.
18¿é 30:5 "They are driven from the community; They shout against them as [against] a thief,
18¿é 30:6 So that they dwell in dreadful valleys, In holes of the earth and of the rocks.
18¿é 30:7 "Among the bushes they cry out; Under the nettles they are gathered together.
18¿é 30:8 "Fools, even those without a name, They were scourged from the land.
18¿é 30:9 "And now I have become their taunt, I have even become a byword to them.
18¿é 30:10 "They abhor me [and] stand aloof from me, And they do not refrain from spitting at my face.
18¿é 30:11 "Because He has loosed His bowstring and afflicted me, They have cast off the bridle before me.
18¿é 30:12 "On the right hand their brood arises; They thrust aside my feet and build up against me their ways of destruction.
18¿é 30:13 "They break up my path, They profit from my destruction, No one restrains them.
18¿é 30:14 "As [through] a wide breach they come, Amid the tempest they roll on.
18¿é 30:15 "Terrors are turned against me, They pursue my honor as the wind, And my prosperity has passed away like a cloud.
18¿é 30:16 "And now my soul is poured out within me; Days of affliction have seized me.
18¿é 30:17 "At night it pierces my bones within me, And my gnawing [pains] take no rest.
18¿é 30:18 "By a great force my garment is distorted; It binds me about as the collar of my coat.
18¿é 30:19 "He has cast me into the mire, And I have become like dust and ashes.
18¿é 30:20 "I cry out to Thee for help, but Thou dost not answer me; I stand up, and Thou dost turn Thy attention against me.
18¿é 30:21 "Thou hast become cruel to me; With the might of Thy hand Thou dost persecute me.
18¿é 30:22 "Thou dost lift me up to the wind [and] cause me to ride; And Thou dost dissolve me in a storm.
18¿é 30:23 "For I know that Thou wilt bring me to death And to the house of meeting for all living.
18¿é 30:24 "Yet does not one in a heap of ruins stretch out [his] hand, Or in his disaster therefore cry out for help?
18¿é 30:25 "Have I not wept for the one whose life is hard? Was not my soul grieved for the needy?
18¿é 30:26 "When I expected good, then evil came; When I waited for light, then darkness came.
18¿é 30:27 "I am seething within, and cannot relax; Days of affliction confront me.
18¿é 30:28 "I go about mourning without comfort; I stand up in the assembly [ and] cry out for help.
18¿é 30:29 "I have become a brother to jackals, And a companion of ostriches.
18¿é 30:30 "My skin turns black on me, And my bones burn with fever.
18¿é 30:31 "Therefore my harp is turned to mourning, And my flute to the sound of those who weep.
18¿é 31:1 "I Have made a covenant with my eyes; How then could I gaze at a virgin?
18¿é 31:2 "And what is the portion of God from above Or the heritage of the Almighty from on high?
18¿é 31:3 "Is it not calamity to the unjust, And disaster to those who work iniquity?
18¿é 31:4 "Does He not see my ways, And number all my steps?
18¿é 31:5 "If I have walked with falsehood, And my foot has hastened after deceit,
18¿é 31:6 Let Him weigh me with accurate scales, And let God know my integrity.
18¿é 31:7 "If my step has turned from the way, Or my heart followed my eyes, Or if any spot has stuck to my hands,
18¿é 31:8 Let me sow and another eat, And let my crops be uprooted.
18¿é 31:9 "If my heart has been enticed by a woman, Or I have lurked at my neighbor's doorway,
18¿é 31:10 May my wife grind for another, And let others kneel down over her.
18¿é 31:11 "For that would be a lustful crime; Moreover, it would be an iniquity [punishable by] judges.
18¿é 31:12 "For it would be fire that consumes to Abaddon, And would uproot all my increase.
18¿é 31:13 "If I have despised the claim of my male or female slaves When they filed a complaint against me,
18¿é 31:14 What then could I do when God arises, And when He calls me to account, what will I answer Him?
18¿é 31:15 "Did not He who made me in the womb make him, And the same one fashion us in the womb?
18¿é 31:16 "If I have kept the poor from [their] desire, Or have caused the eyes of the widow to fail,
18¿é 31:17 Or have eaten my morsel alone, And the orphan has not shared it
18¿é 31:18 (But from my youth he grew up with me as with a father, And from infancy I guided her),
18¿é 31:19 If I have seen anyone perish for lack of clothing, Or that the needy had no covering,
18¿é 31:20 If his loins have not thanked me, And if he has not been warmed with the fleece of my sheep,
18¿é 31:21 If I have lifted up my hand against the orphan, Because I saw I had support in the gate,
18¿é 31:22 Let my shoulder fall from the socket, And my arm be broken off at the elbow.
18¿é 31:23 "For calamity from God is a terror to me, And because of His majesty I can do nothing.
18¿é 31:24 "If I have put my confidence [in] gold, And called fine gold my trust,
18¿é 31:25 If I have gloated because my wealth was great, And because my hand had secured [so] much;
18¿é 31:26 If I have looked at the sun when it shone, Or the moon going in splendor,
18¿é 31:27 And my heart became secretly enticed, And my hand threw a kiss from my mouth,
18¿é 31:28 That too would have been an iniquity [calling for] judgment, For I would have denied God above.
18¿é 31:29 "Have I rejoiced at the extinction of my enemy, Or exulted when evil befell him?
18¿é 31:30 "No, I have not allowed my mouth to sin By asking for his life in a curse.
18¿é 31:31 "Have the men of my tent not said, 'Who can find one who has not been satisfied with his meat'?
18¿é 31:32 "The alien has not lodged outside, [For] I have opened my doors to the traveler.
18¿é 31:33 "Have I covered my transgressions like Adam, By hiding my iniquity in my bosom,
18¿é 31:34 Because I feared the great multitude, And the contempt of families terrified me, And kept silent and did not go out of doors?
18¿é 31:35 "Oh that I had one to hear me! Behold, here is my signature; Let the Almighty answer me! And the indictment which my adversary has written,
18¿é 31:36 Surely I would carry it on my shoulder; I would bind it to myself like a crown.
18¿é 31:37 "I would declare to Him the number of my steps; Like a prince I would approach Him.
18¿é 31:38 "If my land cries out against me, And its furrows weep together;
18¿é 31:39 If I have eaten its fruit without money, Or have caused its owners to lose their lives,
18¿é 31:40 Let briars grow instead of wheat, And stinkweed instead of barley. " The words of Job are ended.
18¿é 32:1 Then these three men ceased answering Job, because he was righteous in his own eyes.
18¿é 32:2 But the anger of Elihu the son of Barachel the Buzite, of the family of Ram burned; against Job his anger burned, because he justified himself before God.
18¿é 32:3 And his anger burned against his three friends because they had found no answer, and yet had condemned Job.
18¿é 32:4 Now Elihu had waited to speak to Job because they were years older than he.
18¿é 32:5 And when Elihu saw that there was no answer in the mouth of the three men his anger burned.
18¿é 32:6 So Elihu the son of Barachel the Buzite spoke out and said, "I am young in years and you are old; Therefore I was shy and afraid to tell you what I think.
18¿é 32:7 "I thought age should speak, And increased years should teach wisdom.
18¿é 32:8 "But it is a spirit in man, And the breath of the Almighty gives them understanding.
18¿é 32:9 "The abundant [in years] may not be wise, Nor may elders understand justice.
18¿é 32:10 "So I say, 'Listen to me, I too will tell what I think.'
18¿é 32:11 "Behold, I waited for your words, I listened to your reasonings, While you pondered what to say.
18¿é 32:12 "I even paid close attention to you, Indeed, there was no one who refuted Job, Not one of you who answered his words.
18¿é 32:13 "Do not say, 'We have found wisdom; God will rout him, not man.'
18¿é 32:14 "For he has not arranged [his] words against me; Nor will I reply to him with your arguments.
18¿é 32:15 "They are dismayed, they answer no more; Words have failed them.
18¿é 32:16 "And shall I wait, because they do not speak, Because they stop [and] answer no more?
18¿é 32:17 "I too will answer my share, I also will tell my opinion.
18¿é 32:18 "For I am full of words; The spirit within me constrains me.
18¿é 32:19 "Behold, my belly is like unvented wine, Like new wineskins it is about to burst.
18¿é 32:20 "Let me speak that I may get relief; Let me open my lips and answer.
18¿é 32:21 "Let me now be partial to no one; Nor flatter [any] man.
18¿é 32:22 "For I do not know how to flatter, [Else] my Maker would soon take me away.
18¿é 33:1 "However now, Job, please hear my speech, And listen to all my words.
18¿é 33:2 "Behold now, I open my mouth, My tongue in my mouth speaks.
18¿é 33:3 "My words are [from] the uprightness of my heart; And my lips speak knowledge sincerely.
18¿é 33:4 "The Spirit of God has made me, And the breath of the Almighty gives me life.
18¿é 33:5 "Refute me if you can; Array yourselves before me, take your stand.
18¿é 33:6 "Behold, I belong to God like you; I too have been formed out of the clay.
18¿é 33:7 "Behold, no fear of me should terrify you, Nor should my pressure weigh heavily on you.
18¿é 33:8 "Surely you have spoken in my hearing, And I have heard the sound of [your] words£º
18¿é 33:9 'I am pure, without transgression; I am innocent and there is no guilt in me.
18¿é 33:10 'Behold, He invents pretexts against me; He counts me as His enemy.
18¿é 33:11 'He puts my feet in the stocks; He watches all my paths.'
18¿é 33:12 "Behold, let me tell you, you are not right in this, For God is greater than man.
18¿é 33:13 "Why do you complain against Him, That He does not give an account of all His doings?
18¿é 33:14 "Indeed God speaks once, Or twice, [yet] no one notices it.
18¿é 33:15 "In a dream, a vision of the night, When sound sleep falls on men, While they slumber in their beds,
18¿é 33:16 Then He opens the ears of men, And seals their instruction,
18¿é 33:17 That He may turn man aside [from his] conduct, And keep man from pride;
18¿é 33:18 He keeps back his soul from the pit, And his life from passing over into Sheol.
18¿é 33:19 "Man is also chastened with pain on his bed, And with unceasing complaint in his bones;
18¿é 33:20 So that his life loathes bread, And his soul favorite food.
18¿é 33:21 "His flesh wastes away from sight, And his bones which were not seen stick out.
18¿é 33:22 "Then his soul draws near to the pit, And his life to those who bring death.
18¿é 33:23 "If there is an angel [as] mediator for him, One out of a thousand, To remind a man what is right for him,
18¿é 33:24 Then let him be gracious to him, and say, 'Deliver him from going down to the pit, I have found a ransom';
18¿é 33:25 Let his flesh become fresher than in youth, Let him return to the days of his youthful vigor;
18¿é 33:26 Then he will pray to God, and He will accept him, That he may see His face with joy, And He may restore His righteousness to man.
18¿é 33:27 "He will sing to men and say, 'I have sinned and perverted what is right, And it is not proper for me.
18¿é 33:28 'He has redeemed my soul from going to the pit, And my life shall see the light.'
18¿é 33:29 "Behold, God does all these oftentimes with men,
18¿é 33:30 To bring back his soul from the pit, That he may be enlightened with the light of life.
18¿é 33:31 "Pay attention, O Job, listen to me; Keep silent and let me speak.
18¿é 33:32 "[Then] if you have anything to say, answer me; Speak, for I desire to justify you.
18¿é 33:33 "If not, listen to me; Keep silent, and I will teach you wisdom."
18¿é 34:1 Then Elihu continued and said,
18¿é 34:2 "Hear my words, you wise men, And listen to me, you who know.
18¿é 34:3 "For the ear tests words, As the palate tastes food.
18¿é 34:4 "Let us choose for ourselves what is right; Let us know among ourselves what is good.
18¿é 34:5 "For Job has said, 'I am righteous, But God has taken away my right;
18¿é 34:6 Should I lie concerning my right? My wound is incurable, [though I am] without transgression. '
18¿é 34:7 "What man is like Job, Who drinks up derision like water,
18¿é 34:8 Who goes in company with the workers of iniquity, And walks with wicked men?
18¿é 34:9 "For he has said, 'It profits a man nothing When he is pleased with God.'
18¿é 34:10 "Therefore, listen to me, you men of understanding. Far be it from God to do wickedness, And from the Almighty to do wrong.
18¿é 34:11 "For He pays a man according to his work, And makes him find it according to his way.
18¿é 34:12 "Surely, God will not act wickedly, And the Almighty will not pervert justice.
18¿é 34:13 "Who gave Him authority over the earth? And who has laid [on Him] the whole world?
18¿é 34:14 "If He should determine to do so, If He should gather to Himself His spirit and His breath,
18¿é 34:15 All flesh would perish together, And man would return to dust.
18¿é 34:16 "But if [you have] understanding, hear this; Listen to the sound of my words.
18¿é 34:17 "Shall one who hates justice rule? And will you condemn a righteous mighty one,
18¿é 34:18 Who says to a king, 'Worthless one,' To nobles, 'Wicked ones';
18¿é 34:19 Who shows no partiality to princes, Nor regards the rich above the poor, For they all are the work of His hands?
