20Àá 1:1 The proverbs of Solomon the son of David, king of Israel£º
20Àá 1:2 To know wisdom and instruction, To discern the sayings of understanding,
20Àá 1:3 To receive instruction in wise behavior, Righteousness, justice and equity;
20Àá 1:4 To give prudence to the naive, To the youth knowledge and discretion,
20Àá 1:5 A wise man will hear and increase in learning, And a man of understanding will acquire wise counsel,
20Àá 1:6 To understand a proverb and a figure, The words of the wise and their riddles.
20Àá 1:7 The fear of the LORD is the beginning of knowledge; Fools despise wisdom and instruction.
20Àá 1:8 Hear, my son, your father's instruction, And do not forsake your mother's teaching;
20Àá 1:9 Indeed, they are a graceful wreath to your head, And ornaments about your neck.
20Àá 1:10 My son, if sinners entice you, Do not consent.
20Àá 1:11 If they say, "Come with us, Let us lie in wait for blood, Let us ambush the innocent without cause;
20Àá 1:12 Let us swallow them alive like Sheol, Even whole, as those who go down to the pit;
20Àá 1:13 We shall find all [kinds] of precious wealth, We shall fill our houses with spoil;
20Àá 1:14 Throw in your lot with us, We shall all have one purse, "
20Àá 1:15 My son, do not walk in the way with them. Keep your feet from their path,
20Àá 1:16 For their feet run to evil, And they hasten to shed blood.
20Àá 1:17 Indeed, it is useless to spread the net In the eyes of any bird;
20Àá 1:18 But they lie in wait for their own blood; They ambush their own lives.
20Àá 1:19 So are the ways of everyone who gains by violence; It takes away the life of its possessors.
20Àá 1:20 Wisdom shouts in the street, She lifts her voice in the square;
20Àá 1:21 At the head of the noisy [streets] she cries out; At the entrance of the gates in the city, she utters her sayings£º
20Àá 1:22 "How long, O naive ones, will you love simplicity? And scoffers delight themselves in scoffing, And fools hate knowledge?
20Àá 1:23 "Turn to my reproof, Behold, I will pour out my spirit on you; I will make my words known to you.
20Àá 1:24 "Because I called, and you refused; I stretched out my hand, and no one paid attention;
20Àá 1:25 And you neglected all my counsel, And did not want my reproof;
20Àá 1:26 I will even laugh at your calamity; I will mock when your dread comes,
20Àá 1:27 When your dread comes like a storm, And your calamity comes on like a whirlwind, When distress [and] anguish come on you.
20Àá 1:28 "Then they will call on me, but I will not answer; They will seek me diligently, but they shall not find me,
20Àá 1:29 Because they hated knowledge, And did not choose the fear of the LORD.
20Àá 1:30 "They would not accept my counsel, They spurned all my reproof.
20Àá 1:31 "So they shall eat of the fruit of their own way, And be satiated with their own devices.
20Àá 1:32 "For the waywardness of the naive shall kill them, And the complacency of fools shall destroy them.
20Àá 1:33 "But he who listens to me shall live securely, And shall be at ease from the dread of evil."
20Àá 2:1 My son, if you will receive my sayings, And treasure my commandments within you,
20Àá 2:2 Make your ear attentive to wisdom, Incline your heart to understanding;
20Àá 2:3 For if you cry for discernment, Lift your voice for understanding;
20Àá 2:4 If you seek her as silver, And search for her as for hidden treasures;
20Àá 2:5 Then you will discern the fear of the LORD, And discover the knowledge of God.
20Àá 2:6 For the LORD gives wisdom; From His mouth [come] knowledge and understanding.
20Àá 2:7 He stores up sound wisdom for the upright; [He is] a shield to those who walk in integrity,
20Àá 2:8 Guarding the paths of justice, And He preserves the way of His godly ones.
20Àá 2:9 Then you will discern righteousness and justice And equity [and] every good course.
20Àá 2:10 For wisdom will enter your heart, And knowledge will be pleasant to your soul;
20Àá 2:11 Discretion will guard you, Understanding will watch over you,
20Àá 2:12 To deliver you from the way of evil, From the man who speaks perverse things;
20Àá 2:13 From those who leave the paths of uprightness, To walk in the ways of darkness;
20Àá 2:14 Who delight in doing evil, And rejoice in the perversity of evil;
20Àá 2:15 Whose paths are crooked, And who are devious in their ways;
20Àá 2:16 To deliver you from the strange woman, From the adulteress who flatters with her words;
20Àá 2:17 That leaves the companion of her youth, And forgets the covenant of her God;
20Àá 2:18 For her house sinks down to death, And her tracks [lead] to the dead;
20Àá 2:19 None who go to her return again, Nor do they reach the paths of life.
20Àá 2:20 So you will walk in the way of good men, And keep to the paths of the righteous.
20Àá 2:21 For the upright will live in the land, And the blameless will remain in it;
20Àá 2:22 But the wicked will be cut off from the land, And the treacherous will be uprooted from it.
20Àá 3:1 My son, do not forget my teaching, But let your heart keep my commandments;
20Àá 3:2 For length of days and years of life, And peace they will add to you.
20Àá 3:3 Do not let kindness and truth leave you; Bind them around your neck, Write them on the tablet of your heart.
20Àá 3:4 So you will find favor and good repute In the sight of God and man.
20Àá 3:5 Trust in the LORD with all your heart, And do not lean on your own understanding.
20Àá 3:6 In all your ways acknowledge Him, And He will make your paths straight.
20Àá 3:7 Do not be wise in your own eyes; Fear the LORD and turn away from evil.
20Àá 3:8 It will be healing to your body, And refreshment to your bones.
20Àá 3:9 Honor the LORD from your wealth, And from the first of all your produce;
20Àá 3:10 So your barns will be filled with plenty, And your vats will overflow with new wine.
20Àá 3:11 My son, do not reject the discipline of the LORD, Or loathe His reproof,
20Àá 3:12 For whom the LORD loves He reproves, Even as a father, the son in whom he delights.
20Àá 3:13 How blessed is the man who finds wisdom, And the man who gains understanding.
20Àá 3:14 For its profit is better than the profit of silver, And its gain than fine gold.
20Àá 3:15 She is more precious than jewels; And nothing you desire compares with her.
20Àá 3:16 Long life is in her right hand; In her left hand are riches and honor.
20Àá 3:17 Her ways are pleasant ways, And all her paths are peace.
20Àá 3:18 She is a tree of life to those who take hold of her, And happy are all who hold her fast.
20Àá 3:19 The LORD by wisdom founded the earth; By understanding He established the heavens.
20Àá 3:20 By His knowledge the deeps were broken up, And the skies drip with dew.
20Àá 3:21 My son, let them not depart from your sight; Keep sound wisdom and discretion,
20Àá 3:22 So they will be life to your soul, And adornment to your neck.
20Àá 3:23 Then you will walk in your way securely, And your foot will not stumble.
20Àá 3:24 When you lie down, you will not be afraid; When you lie down, your sleep will be sweet.
20Àá 3:25 Do not be afraid of sudden fear, Nor of the onslaught of the wicked when it comes;
20Àá 3:26 For the LORD will be your confidence, And will keep your foot from being caught.
20Àá 3:27 Do not withhold good from those to whom it is due, When it is in your power to do [it.]
20Àá 3:28 Do not say to your neighbor, "Go, and come back, And tomorrow I will give [it,]" When you have it with you.
20Àá 3:29 Do not devise harm against your neighbor, While he lives in security beside you.
20Àá 3:30 Do not contend with a man without cause, If he has done you no harm.
20Àá 3:31 Do not envy a man of violence, And do not choose any of his ways.
20Àá 3:32 For the crooked [man] is an abomination to the LORD; But He is intimate with the upright.
20Àá 3:33 The curse of the LORD is on the house of the wicked, But He blesses the dwelling of the righteous.
20Àá 3:34 Though He scoffs at the scoffers, Yet He gives grace to the afflicted.
20Àá 3:35 The wise will inherit honor, But fools display dishonor.
20Àá 4:1 Hear, [O] sons, the instruction of a father, And give attention that you may gain understanding,
20Àá 4:2 For I give you sound teaching; Do not abandon my instruction.
20Àá 4:3 When I was a son to my father, Tender and the only son in the sight of my mother,
20Àá 4:4 Then he taught me and said to me, "Let your heart hold fast my words; Keep my commandments and live;
20Àá 4:5 Acquire wisdom! Acquire understanding! Do not forget, nor turn away from the words of my mouth.
20Àá 4:6 "Do not forsake her, and she will guard you; Love her, and she will watch over you.
20Àá 4:7 "The beginning of wisdom [is:] Acquire wisdom; And with all your acquiring, get understanding.
20Àá 4:8 "Prize her, and she will exalt you; She will honor you if you embrace her.
20Àá 4:9 "She will place on your head a garland of grace; She will present you with a crown of beauty."
20Àá 4:10 Hear, my son, and accept my sayings, And the years of your life will be many.
20Àá 4:11 I have directed you in the way of wisdom; I have led you in upright paths.
20Àá 4:12 When you walk, your steps will not be impeded; And if you run, you will not stumble.
20Àá 4:13 Take hold of instruction; do not let go. Guard her, for she is your life.
20Àá 4:14 Do not enter the path of the wicked, And do not proceed in the way of evil men.
20Àá 4:15 Avoid it, do not pass by it; Turn away from it and pass on.
20Àá 4:16 For they cannot sleep unless they do evil; And they are robbed of sleep unless they make [someone] stumble.
20Àá 4:17 For they eat the bread of wickedness, And drink the wine of violence.
20Àá 4:18 But the path of the righteous is like the light of dawn, That shines brighter and brighter until the full day.
20Àá 4:19 The way of the wicked is like darkness; They do not know over what they stumble.
20Àá 4:20 My son, give attention to my words; Incline your ear to my sayings.
20Àá 4:21 Do not let them depart from your sight; Keep them in the midst of your heart.
20Àá 4:22 For they are life to those who find them, And health to all their whole body.
20Àá 4:23 Watch over your heart with all diligence, For from it [flow] the springs of life.
20Àá 4:24 Put away from you a deceitful mouth, And put devious lips far from you.
20Àá 4:25 Let your eyes look directly ahead, And let your gaze be fixed straight in front of you.
20Àá 4:26 Watch the path of your feet, And all your ways will be established.
20Àá 4:27 Do not turn to the right nor to the left; Turn your foot from evil.
20Àá 5:1 My son, give attention to my wisdom, Incline your ear to my understanding;
20Àá 5:2 That you may observe discretion, And your lips may reserve knowledge.
20Àá 5:3 For the lips of an adulteress drip honey, And smoother than oil is her speech;
20Àá 5:4 But in the end she is bitter as wormwood, Sharp as a two-edged sword.
20Àá 5:5 Her feet go down to death, Her steps lay hold of Sheol.
20Àá 5:6 She does not ponder the path of life; Her ways are unstable, she does not know [it].
20Àá 5:7 Now then, [my] sons, listen to me, And do not depart from the words of my mouth.
20Àá 5:8 Keep your way far from her, And do not go near the door of her house,
20Àá 5:9 Lest you give your vigor to others, And your years to the cruel one;
20Àá 5:10 Lest strangers be filled with your strength, And your hard-earned goods [go] to the house of an alien;
20Àá 5:11 And you groan at your latter end, When your flesh and your body are consumed;
20Àá 5:12 And you say, "How I have hated instruction! And my heart spurned reproof!
20Àá 5:13 "And I have not listened to the voice of my teachers, Nor inclined my ear to my instructors!
20Àá 5:14 "I was almost in utter ruin In the midst of the assembly and congregation."
20Àá 5:15 Drink water from your own cistern, And fresh water from your own well.
20Àá 5:16 Should your springs be dispersed abroad, Streams of water in the streets?
20Àá 5:17 Let them be yours alone, And not for strangers with you.
20Àá 5:18 Let your fountain be blessed, And rejoice in the wife of your youth.
20Àá 5:19 [As] a loving hind and a graceful doe, Let her breasts satisfy you at all times; Be exhilarated always with her love.
20Àá 5:20 For why should you, my son, be exhilarated with an adulteress, And embrace the bosom of a foreigner?
20Àá 5:21 For the ways of a man are before the eyes of the LORD, And He watches all his paths.
20Àá 5:22 His own iniquities will capture the wicked, And he will be held with the cords of his sin.
20Àá 5:23 He will die for lack of instruction, And in the greatness of his folly he will go astray.
20Àá 6:1 My son, if you have become surety for your neighbor, Have given a pledge for a stranger,
20Àá 6:2 [If] you have been snared with the words of your mouth, Have been caught with the words of your mouth,
20Àá 6:3 Do this then, my son, and deliver yourself; Since you have come into the hand of your neighbor, Go, humble yourself, and importune your neighbor.
20Àá 6:4 Do not give sleep to your eyes, Nor slumber to your eyelids;
20Àá 6:5 Deliver yourself like a gazelle from [the hunter's] hand, And like a bird from the hand of the fowler.
20Àá 6:6 Go to the ant, O sluggard, Observe her ways and be wise,
20Àá 6:7 Which, having no chief, Officer or ruler,
20Àá 6:8 Prepares her food in the summer, [And] gathers her provision in the harvest.
20Àá 6:9 How long will you lie down, O sluggard? When will you arise from your sleep?
20Àá 6:10 "A little sleep, a little slumber, A little folding of the hands to rest"--
20Àá 6:11 And your poverty will come in like a vagabond, And your need like an armed man.
20Àá 6:12 A worthless person, a wicked man, Is the one who walks with a false mouth,
20Àá 6:13 Who winks with his eyes, who signals with his feet, Who points with his fingers;
20Àá 6:14 Who [with] perversity in his heart devises evil continually, Who spreads strife.
20Àá 6:15 Therefore his calamity will come suddenly; Instantly he will be broken, and there will be no healing.
20Àá 6:16 There are six things which the LORD hates, Yes, seven which are an abomination to Him£º
20Àá 6:17 Haughty eyes, a lying tongue, And hands that shed innocent blood,
20Àá 6:18 A heart that devises wicked plans, Feet that run rapidly to evil,
20Àá 6:19 A false witness [who] utters lies, And one who spreads strife among brothers.
20Àá 6:20 My son, observe the commandment of your father, And do not forsake the teaching of your mother;
20Àá 6:21 Bind them continually on your heart; Tie them around your neck.
20Àá 6:22 When you walk about, they will guide you; When you sleep, they will watch over you; And when you awake, they will talk to you.
20Àá 6:23 For the commandment is a lamp, and the teaching is light; And reproofs for discipline are the way of life,
20Àá 6:24 To keep you from the evil woman, From the smooth tongue of the adulteress.
20Àá 6:25 Do not desire her beauty in your heart, Nor let her catch you with her eyelids.
20Àá 6:26 For on account of a harlot [one is reduced] to a loaf of bread, And an adulteress hunts for the precious life.
20Àá 6:27 Can a man take fire in his bosom, And his clothes not be burned?
20Àá 6:28 Or can a man walk on hot coals, And his feet not be scorched?
20Àá 6:29 So is the one who goes in to his neighbor's wife; Whoever touches her will not go unpunished.
20Àá 6:30 Men do not despise a thief if he steals To satisfy himself when he is hungry;
20Àá 6:31 But when he is found, he must repay sevenfold; He must give all the substance of his house.
20Àá 6:32 The one who commits adultery with a woman is lacking sense; He who would destroy himself does it.
20Àá 6:33 Wounds and disgrace he will find, And his reproach will not be blotted out.
20Àá 6:34 For jealousy enrages a man, And he will not spare in the day of vengeance.
20Àá 6:35 He will not accept any ransom, Nor will he be content though you give many gifts.
20Àá 7:1 My son, keep my words, And treasure my commandments within you.
20Àá 7:2 Keep my commandments and live, And my teaching as the apple of your eye.
20Àá 7:3 Bind them on your fingers; Write them on the tablet of your heart.
20Àá 7:4 Say to wisdom, "You are my sister," And call understanding [your] intimate friend;
20Àá 7:5 That they may keep you from an adulteress, From the foreigner who flatters with her words.
20Àá 7:6 For at the window of my house I looked out through my lattice,
20Àá 7:7 And I saw among the naive, I discerned among the youths, A young man lacking sense,
20Àá 7:8 Passing through the street near her corner; And he takes the way to her house,
20Àá 7:9 In the twilight, in the evening, In the middle of the night and [in] the darkness.
20Àá 7:10 And behold, a woman [comes] to meet him, Dressed as a harlot and cunning of heart.
20Àá 7:11 She is boisterous and rebellious; Her feet do not remain at home;
20Àá 7:12 [She is] now in the streets, now in the squares, And lurks by every corner.
20Àá 7:13 So she seizes him and kisses him, And with a brazen face she says to him£º
20Àá 7:14 "I was due to offer peace offerings; Today I have paid my vows.
20Àá 7:15 "Therefore I have come out to meet you, To seek your presence earnestly, and I have found you.
20Àá 7:16 "I have spread my couch with coverings, With colored linens of Egypt.
20Àá 7:17 "I have sprinkled my bed With myrrh, aloes and cinnamon.
20Àá 7:18 "Come, let us drink our fill of love until morning; Let us delight ourselves with caresses.
20Àá 7:19 "For the man is not at home, He has gone on a long journey;
20Àá 7:20 He has taken a bag of money with him, At full moon he will come home. "
20Àá 7:21 With her many persuasions she entices him; With her flattering lips she seduces him.
20Àá 7:22 Suddenly he follows her, As an ox goes to the slaughter, Or as [one in] fetters to the discipline of a fool,
20Àá 7:23 Until an arrow pierces through his liver; As a bird hastens to the snare, So he does not know that it [will cost him] his life.
20Àá 7:24 Now therefore, [my] sons, listen to me, And pay attention to the words of my mouth.
20Àá 7:25 Do not let your heart turn aside to her ways, Do not stray into her paths.
20Àá 7:26 For many are the victims she has cast down, And numerous are all her slain.
20Àá 7:27 Her house is the way to Sheol, Descending to the chambers of death.
20Àá 8:1 Does not wisdom call, And understanding lift up her voice?
20Àá 8:2 On top of the heights beside the way, Where the paths meet, she takes her stand;
20Àá 8:3 Beside the gates, at the opening to the city, At the entrance of the doors, she cries out£º
20Àá 8:4 "To you, O men, I call, And my voice is to the sons of men.
20Àá 8:5 "O naive ones, discern prudence; And, O fools, discern wisdom.
20Àá 8:6 "Listen, for I shall speak noble things; And the opening of my lips [ will produce] right things.
20Àá 8:7 "For my mouth will utter truth; And wickedness is an abomination to my lips.
20Àá 8:8 "All the utterances of my mouth are in righteousness; There is nothing crooked or perverted in them.
20Àá 8:9 "They are all straightforward to him who understands, And right to those who find knowledge.
20Àá 8:10 "Take my instruction, and not silver, And knowledge rather than choicest gold.
20Àá 8:11 "For wisdom is better than jewels; And all desirable things can not compare with her.
20Àá 8:12 "I, wisdom, dwell with prudence, And I find knowledge [and] discretion.
20Àá 8:13 "The fear of the LORD is to hate evil; Pride and arrogance and the evil way, And the perverted mouth, I hate.
20Àá 8:14 "Counsel is mine and sound wisdom; I am understanding, power is mine.
20Àá 8:15 "By me kings reign, And rulers decree justice.
20Àá 8:16 "By me princes rule, and nobles, All who judge rightly.
20Àá 8:17 "I love those who love me; And those who diligently seek me will find me.
20Àá 8:18 "Riches and honor are with me, Enduring wealth and righteousness.
20Àá 8:19 "My fruit is better than gold, even pure gold, And my yield than choicest silver.
20Àá 8:20 "I walk in the way of righteousness, In the midst of the paths of justice,
20Àá 8:21 To endow those who love me with wealth, That I may fill their treasuries.
20Àá 8:22 "The LORD possessed me at the beginning of His way, Before His works of old.
20Àá 8:23 "From everlasting I was established, From the beginning, from the earliest times of the earth.
20Àá 8:24 "When there were no depths I was brought forth, When there were no springs abounding with water.
20Àá 8:25 "Before the mountains were settled, Before the hills I was brought forth;
20Àá 8:26 While He had not yet made the earth and the fields, Nor the first dust of the world.
20Àá 8:27 "When He established the heavens, I was there, When He inscribed a circle on the face of the deep,
20Àá 8:28 When He made firm the skies above, When the springs of the deep became fixed,
20Àá 8:29 When He set for the sea its boundary, So that the water should not transgress His command, When He marked out the foundations of the earth;
20Àá 8:30 Then I was beside Him, [as] a master workman; And I was daily [His] delight, Rejoicing always before Him,
20Àá 8:31 Rejoicing in the world, His earth, And [having] my delight in the sons of men.
20Àá 8:32 "Now therefore, [O] sons, listen to me, For blessed are they who keep my ways.
20Àá 8:33 "Heed instruction and be wise, And do not neglect [it.]
20Àá 8:34 "Blessed is the man who listens to me, Watching daily at my gates, Waiting at my doorposts.
20Àá 8:35 "For he who finds me finds life, And obtains favor from the LORD.
20Àá 8:36 "But he who sins against me injures himself; All those who hate me love death."
20Àá 9:1 Wisdom has built her house, She has hewn out her seven pillars;
20Àá 9:2 She has prepared her food, she has mixed her wine; She has also set her table;
20Àá 9:3 She has sent out her maidens, she calls From the tops of the heights of the city£º
20Àá 9:4 "Whoever is naive, let him turn in here!" To him who lacks understanding she says,
20Àá 9:5 "Come, eat of my food, And drink of the wine I have mixed.
20Àá 9:6 "Forsake [your] folly and live, And proceed in the way of understanding."
20Àá 9:7 He who corrects a scoffer gets dishonor for himself, And he who reproves a wicked man [gets] insults for himself.
20Àá 9:8 Do not reprove a scoffer, lest he hate you, Reprove a wise man, and he will love you.
20Àá 9:9 Give [instruction] to a wise man, and he will be still wiser, Teach a righteous man, and he will increase [his] learning.
20Àá 9:10 The fear of the LORD is the beginning of wisdom, And the knowledge of the Holy One is understanding.
20Àá 9:11 For by me your days will be multiplied, And years of life will be added to you.
20Àá 9:12 If you are wise, you are wise for yourself, And if you scoff, you alone will bear it.
20Àá 9:13 The woman of folly is boisterous, [She is] naive, and knows nothing.
20Àá 9:14 And she sits at the doorway of her house, On a seat by the high places of the city,
20Àá 9:15 Calling to those who pass by, Who are making their paths straight£º
20Àá 9:16 "Whoever is naive, let him turn in here," And to him who lacks understanding she says,
20Àá 9:17 "Stolen water is sweet; And bread [eaten] in secret is pleasant."
20Àá 9:18 But he does not know that the dead are there, [That] her guests are in the depths of Sheol.
20Àá 10:1 The proverbs of Solomon. A wise son makes a father glad, But a foolish son is a grief to his mother.
20Àá 10:2 Ill-gotten gains do not profit, But righteousness delivers from death.
20Àá 10:3 The LORD will not allow the righteous to hunger, But He will thrust [aside] the craving of the wicked.
20Àá 10:4 Poor is he who works with a negligent hand, But the hand of the diligent makes rich.
20Àá 10:5 He who gathers in summer is a son who acts wisely, [But] he who sleeps in harvest is a son who acts shamefully.
20Àá 10:6 Blessings are on the head of the righteous, But the mouth of the wicked conceals violence.
20Àá 10:7 The memory of the righteous is blessed, But the name of the wicked will rot.
20Àá 10:8 The wise of heart will receive commands, But a babbling fool will be thrown down.
20Àá 10:9 He who walks in integrity walks securely, But he who perverts his ways will be found out.
20Àá 10:10 He who winks the eye causes trouble, And a babbling fool will be thrown down.
20Àá 10:11 The mouth of the righteous is a fountain of life, But the mouth of the wicked conceals violence.
20Àá 10:12 Hatred stirs up strife, But love covers all transgressions.
20Àá 10:13 On the lips of the discerning, wisdom is found, But a rod is for the back of him who lacks understanding.
20Àá 10:14 Wise men store up knowledge, But with the mouth of the foolish, ruin is at hand.
20Àá 10:15 The rich man's wealth is his fortress, The ruin of the poor is their poverty.
20Àá 10:16 The wages of the righteous is life, The income of the wicked, punishment.
20Àá 10:17 He is [on] the path of life who heeds instruction, But he who forsakes reproof goes astray.
20Àá 10:18 He who conceals hatred [has] lying lips, And he who spreads slander is a fool.
20Àá 10:19 When there are many words, transgression is unavoidable, But he who restrains his lips is wise.
20Àá 10:20 The tongue of the righteous is [as] choice silver, The heart of the wicked is [worth] little.
20Àá 10:21 The lips of the righteous feed many, But fools die for lack of understanding.
20Àá 10:22 It is the blessing of the LORD that makes rich, And He adds no sorrow to it.
20Àá 10:23 Doing wickedness is like sport to a fool; And [so is] wisdom to a man of understanding.
20Àá 10:24 What the wicked fears will come upon him, And the desire of the righteous will be granted.
20Àá 10:25 When the whirlwind passes, the wicked is no more, But the righteous [has] an everlasting foundation.
20Àá 10:26 Like vinegar to the teeth and smoke to the eyes, So is the lazy one to those who send him.
20Àá 10:27 The fear of the LORD prolongs life, But the years of the wicked will be shortened.
20Àá 10:28 The hope of the righteous is gladness, But the expectation of the wicked perishes.
20Àá 10:29 The way of the LORD is a stronghold to the upright, But ruin to the workers of iniquity.
20Àá 10:30 The righteous will never be shaken, But the wicked will not dwell in the land.
20Àá 10:31 The mouth of the righteous flows with wisdom, But the perverted tongue will be cut out.
20Àá 10:32 The lips of the righteous bring forth what is acceptable, But the mouth of the wicked, what is perverted.
20Àá 11:1 A false balance is an abomination to the LORD, But a just weight is His delight.
20Àá 11:2 When pride comes, then comes dishonor, But with the humble is wisdom.
20Àá 11:3 The integrity of the upright will guide them, But the falseness of the treacherous will destroy them.
20Àá 11:4 Riches do not profit in the day of wrath, But righteousness delivers from death.
20Àá 11:5 The righteousness of the blameless will smooth his way, But the wicked will fall by his own wickedness.
20Àá 11:6 The righteousness of the upright will deliver them, But the treacherous will be caught by [their own] greed.
20Àá 11:7 When a wicked man dies, [his] expectation will perish, And the hope of strong men perishes.
20Àá 11:8 The righteous is delivered from trouble, But the wicked takes his place.
20Àá 11:9 With [his] mouth the godless man destroys his neighbor, But through knowledge the righteous will be delivered.
20Àá 11:10 When it goes well with the righteous, the city rejoices, And when the wicked perish, there is glad shouting.
20Àá 11:11 By the blessing of the upright a city is exalted, But by the mouth of the wicked it is torn down.
20Àá 11:12 He who despises his neighbor lacks sense, But a man of understanding keeps silent.
20Àá 11:13 He who goes about as a talebearer reveals secrets, But he who is trustworthy conceals a matter.
20Àá 11:14 Where there is no guidance, the people fall, But in abundance of counselors there is victory.
20Àá 11:15 He who is surety for a stranger will surely suffer for it, But he who hates going surety is safe.
20Àá 11:16 A gracious woman attains honor, And violent men attain riches.
20Àá 11:17 The merciful man does himself good, But the cruel man does himself harm.
20Àá 11:18 The wicked earns deceptive wages, But he who sows righteousness [gets] a true reward.
20Àá 11:19 He who is steadfast in righteousness [will attain] to life, And he who pursues evil [will bring about] his own death.
20Àá 11:20 The perverse in heart are an abomination to the LORD, But the blameless in [their] walk are His delight.
20Àá 11:21 Assuredly, the evil man will not go unpunished, But the descendants of the righteous will be delivered.
20Àá 11:22 [As] a ring of gold in a swine's snout, [So is] a beautiful woman who lacks discretion.
20Àá 11:23 The desire of the righteous is only good, [But] the expectation of the wicked is wrath.
20Àá 11:24 There is one who scatters, yet increases all the more, And there is one who withholds what is justly due, but [it results] only in want.
20Àá 11:25 The generous man will be prosperous, And he who waters will himself be watered.
20Àá 11:26 He who withholds grain, the people will curse him, But blessing will be on the head of him who sells [it.]
20Àá 11:27 He who diligently seeks good seeks favor, But he who searches after evil, it will come to him.
20Àá 11:28 He who trusts in his riches will fall, But the righteous will flourish like the [green] leaf.
20Àá 11:29 He who troubles his own house will inherit wind, And the foolish will be servant to the wisehearted.
20Àá 11:30 The fruit of the righteous is a tree of life, And he who is wise wins souls.
20Àá 11:31 If the righteous will be rewarded in the earth, How much more the wicked and the sinner!
20Àá 12:1 Whoever loves discipline loves knowledge, But he who hates reproof is stupid.
20Àá 12:2 A good man will obtain favor from the LORD, But He will condemn a man who devises evil.
20Àá 12:3 A man will not be established by wickedness, But the root of the righteous will not be moved.
20Àá 12:4 An excellent wife is the crown of her husband, But she who shames [ him] is as rottenness in his bones.
20Àá 12:5 The thoughts of the righteous are just, [But] the counsels of the wicked are deceitful.
20Àá 12:6 The words of the wicked lie in wait for blood, But the mouth of the upright will deliver them.
20Àá 12:7 The wicked are overthrown and are no more, But the house of the righteous will stand.
20Àá 12:8 A man will be praised according to his insight, But one of perverse mind will be despised.
20Àá 12:9 Better is he who is lightly esteemed and has a servant, Than he who honors himself and lacks bread.
20Àá 12:10 A righteous man has regard for the life of his beast, But the compassion of the wicked is cruel.
20Àá 12:11 He who tills his land will have plenty of bread, But he who pursues vain [things] lacks sense.
20Àá 12:12 The wicked desires the booty of evil men, But the root of the righteous yields [fruit.]
20Àá 12:13 An evil man is ensnared by the transgression of his lips, But the righteous will escape from trouble.
20Àá 12:14 A man will be satisfied with good by the fruit of his words, And the deeds of a man's hands will return to him.
20Àá 12:15 The way of a fool is right in his own eyes, But a wise man is he who listens to counsel.
20Àá 12:16 A fool's vexation is known at once, But a prudent man conceals dishonor.
20Àá 12:17 He who speaks truth tells what is right, But a false witness, deceit.
20Àá 12:18 There is one who speaks rashly like the thrusts of a sword, But the tongue of the wise brings healing.
20Àá 12:19 Truthful lips will be established forever, But a lying tongue is only for a moment.
20Àá 12:20 Deceit is in the heart of those who devise evil, But counselors of peace have joy.
20Àá 12:21 No harm befalls the righteous, But the wicked are filled with trouble.
20Àá 12:22 Lying lips are an abomination to the LORD, But those who deal faithfully are His delight.
20Àá 12:23 A prudent man conceals knowledge, But the heart of fools proclaims folly.
20Àá 12:24 The hand of the diligent will rule, But the slack [hand] will be put to forced labor.
20Àá 12:25 Anxiety in the heart of a man weighs it down, But a good word makes it glad.
20Àá 12:26 The righteous is a guide to his neighbor, But the way of the wicked leads them astray.
20Àá 12:27 A slothful man does not roast his prey, But the precious possession of a man [is] diligence.
20Àá 12:28 In the way of righteousness is life, And in [its] pathway there is no death.
20Àá 13:1 A wise son [accepts his] father's discipline, But a scoffer does not listen to rebuke.
20Àá 13:2 From the fruit of a man's mouth he enjoys good, But the desire of the treacherous is violence.
20Àá 13:3 The one who guards his mouth preserves his life; The one who opens wide his lips comes to ruin.
20Àá 13:4 The soul of the sluggard craves and [gets] nothing, But the soul of the diligent is made fat.
20Àá 13:5 A righteous man hates falsehood, But a wicked man acts disgustingly and shamefully.
20Àá 13:6 Righteousness guards the one whose way is blameless, But wickedness subverts the sinner.
20Àá 13:7 There is one who pretends to be rich, but has nothing; [Another] pretends to be poor, but has great wealth.
20Àá 13:8 The ransom of a man's life is his riches, But the poor hears no rebuke.
20Àá 13:9 The light of the righteous rejoices, But the lamp of the wicked goes out.
20Àá 13:10 Through presumption comes nothing but strife, But with those who receive counsel is wisdom.
20Àá 13:11 Wealth [obtained] by fraud dwindles, But the one who gathers by labor increases [it.]
20Àá 13:12 Hope deferred makes the heart sick, But desire fulfilled is a tree of life.
20Àá 13:13 The one who despises the word will be in debt to it, But the one who fears the commandment will be rewarded.
20Àá 13:14 The teaching of the wise is a fountain of life, To turn aside from the snares of death.
20Àá 13:15 Good understanding produces favor, But the way of the treacherous is hard.
20Àá 13:16 Every prudent man acts with knowledge, But a fool displays folly.
20Àá 13:17 A wicked messenger falls into adversity, But a faithful envoy [brings] healing.
20Àá 13:18 Poverty and shame [will come] to him who neglects discipline, But he who regards reproof will be honored.
20Àá 13:19 Desire realized is sweet to the soul, But it is an abomination to fools to depart from evil.
20Àá 13:20 He who walks with wise men will be wise, But the companion of fools will suffer harm.
20Àá 13:21 Adversity pursues sinners, But the righteous will be rewarded with prosperity.
20Àá 13:22 A good man leaves an inheritance to his children's children, And the wealth of the sinner is stored up for the righteous.
20Àá 13:23 Abundant food [is in] the fallow ground of the poor, But it is swept away by injustice.
20Àá 13:24 He who spares his rod hates his son, But he who loves him disciplines him diligently.
20Àá 13:25 The righteous has enough to satisfy his appetite, But the stomach of the wicked is in want.
20Àá 14:1 The wise woman builds her house, But the foolish tears it down with her own hands.
20Àá 14:2 He who walks in his uprightness fears the LORD, But he who is crooked in his ways despises Him.
20Àá 14:3 In the mouth of the foolish is a rod for [his] back, But the lips of the wise will preserve them.
20Àá 14:4 Where no oxen are, the manger is clean, But much increase [comes] by the strength of the ox.
20Àá 14:5 A faithful witness will not lie, But a false witness speaks lies.
20Àá 14:6 A scoffer seeks wisdom, and [finds] none, But knowledge is easy to him who has understanding.
20Àá 14:7 Leave the presence of a fool, Or you will not discern words of knowledge.
20Àá 14:8 The wisdom of the prudent is to understand his way, But the folly of fools is deceit.
20Àá 14:9 Fools mock at sin, But among the upright there is good will.
20Àá 14:10 The heart knows its own bitterness, And a stranger does not share its joy.
20Àá 14:11 The house of the wicked will be destroyed, But the tent of the upright will flourish.
20Àá 14:12 There is a way [which seems] right to a man, But its end is the way of death.
20Àá 14:13 Even in laughter the heart may be in pain, And the end of joy may be grief.
20Àá 14:14 The backslider in heart will have his fill of his own ways, But a good man will [be satisfied] with his.
20Àá 14:15 The naive believes everything, But the prudent man considers his steps.
20Àá 14:16 A wise man is cautious and turns away from evil, But a fool is arrogant and careless.
20Àá 14:17 A quick-tempered man acts foolishly, And a man of evil devices is hated.
20Àá 14:18 The naive inherit folly, But the prudent are crowned with knowledge.
20Àá 14:19 The evil will bow down before the good, And the wicked at the gates of the righteous.
20Àá 14:20 The poor is hated even by his neighbor, But those who love the rich are many.
20Àá 14:21 He who despises his neighbor sins, But happy is he who is gracious to the poor.
20Àá 14:22 Will they not go astray who devise evil? But kindness and truth [will be to] those who devise good.
20Àá 14:23 In all labor there is profit, But mere talk [leads] only to poverty.
20Àá 14:24 The crown of the wise is their riches, [But] the folly of fools is foolishness.
20Àá 14:25 A truthful witness saves lives, But he who speaks lies is treacherous.
20Àá 14:26 In the fear of the LORD there is strong confidence, And his children will have refuge.
20Àá 14:27 The fear of the LORD is a fountain of life, That one may avoid the snares of death.
20Àá 14:28 In a multitude of people is a king's glory, But in the dearth of people is a prince's ruin.
20Àá 14:29 He who is slow to anger has great understanding, But he who is quick-tempered exalts folly.
20Àá 14:30 A tranquil heart is life to the body, But passion is rottenness to the bones.
20Àá 14:31 He who oppresses the poor reproaches his Maker, But he who is gracious to the needy honors Him.
20Àá 14:32 The wicked is thrust down by his wrongdoing, But the righteous has a refuge when he dies.
20Àá 14:33 Wisdom rests in the heart of one who has understanding, But in the bosom of fools it is made known.
20Àá 14:34 Righteousness exalts a nation, But sin is a disgrace to [any] people.
20Àá 14:35 The king's favor is toward a servant who acts wisely, But his anger is toward him who acts shamefully.
20Àá 15:1 A gentle answer turns away wrath, But a harsh word stirs up anger.
20Àá 15:2 The tongue of the wise makes knowledge acceptable, But the mouth of fools spouts folly.
20Àá 15:3 The eyes of the LORD are in every place, Watching the evil and the good.
20Àá 15:4 A soothing tongue is a tree of life, But perversion in it crushes the spirit.
20Àá 15:5 A fool rejects his father's discipline, But he who regards reproof is prudent.
20Àá 15:6 Much wealth is [in] the house of the righteous, But trouble is in the income of the wicked.
20Àá 15:7 The lips of the wise spread knowledge, But the hearts of fools are not so.
20Àá 15:8 The sacrifice of the wicked is an abomination to the LORD, But the prayer of the upright is His delight.
20Àá 15:9 The way of the wicked is an abomination to the LORD, But He loves him who pursues righteousness.
20Àá 15:10 Stern discipline is for him who forsakes the way; He who hates reproof will die.
20Àá 15:11 Sheol and Abaddon [lie open] before the LORD, How much more the hearts of men!
20Àá 15:12 A scoffer does not love one who reproves him, He will not go to the wise.
20Àá 15:13 A joyful heart makes a cheerful face, But when the heart is sad, the spirit is broken.
20Àá 15:14 The mind of the intelligent seeks knowledge, But the mouth of fools feeds on folly.
20Àá 15:15 All the days of the afflicted are bad, But a cheerful heart [has] a continual feast.
20Àá 15:16 Better is a little with the fear of the LORD, Than great treasure and turmoil with it.
20Àá 15:17 Better is a dish of vegetables where love is, Than a fattened ox and hatred with it.
20Àá 15:18 A hot-tempered man stirs up strife, But the slow to anger pacifies contention.
20Àá 15:19 The way of the sluggard is as a hedge of thorns, But the path of the upright is a highway.
20Àá 15:20 A wise son makes a father glad, But a foolish man despises his mother.
20Àá 15:21 Folly is joy to him who lacks sense, But a man of understanding walks straight.
20Àá 15:22 Without consultation, plans are frustrated, But with many counselors they succeed.
20Àá 15:23 A man has joy in an apt answer, And how delightful is a timely word!
20Àá 15:24 The path of life [leads] upward for the wise, That he may keep away from Sheol below.
20Àá 15:25 The LORD will tear down the house of the proud, But He will establish the boundary of the widow.
20Àá 15:26 Evil plans are an abomination to the LORD, But pleasant words are pure.
20Àá 15:27 He who profits illicitly troubles his own house, But he who hates bribes will live.
20Àá 15:28 The heart of the righteous ponders how to answer, But the mouth of the wicked pours out evil things.
20Àá 15:29 The LORD is far from the wicked, But He hears the prayer of the righteous.
20Àá 15:30 Bright eyes gladden the heart; Good news puts fat on the bones.
20Àá 15:31 He whose ear listens to the life-giving reproof Will dwell among the wise.
20Àá 15:32 He who neglects discipline despises himself, But he who listens to reproof acquires understanding.
20Àá 15:33 The fear of the LORD is the instruction for wisdom, And before honor [comes] humility.
20Àá 16:1 The plans of the heart belong to man, But the answer of the tongue is from the LORD.
20Àá 16:2 All the ways of a man are clean in his own sight, But the LORD weighs the motives.
20Àá 16:3 Commit your works to the LORD, And your plans will be established.
20Àá 16:4 The LORD has made everything for its own purpose, Even the wicked for the day of evil.
20Àá 16:5 Everyone who is proud in heart is an abomination to the LORD; Assuredly, he will not be unpunished.
20Àá 16:6 By lovingkindness and truth iniquity is atoned for, And by the fear of the LORD one keeps away from evil.
20Àá 16:7 When a man's ways are pleasing to the LORD, He makes even his enemies to be at peace with him.
20Àá 16:8 Better is a little with righteousness Than great income with injustice.
20Àá 16:9 The mind of man plans his way, But the LORD directs his steps.
20Àá 16:10 A divine decision is in the lips of the king; His mouth should not err in judgment.
20Àá 16:11 A just balance and scales belong to the LORD; All the weights of the bag are His concern.
20Àá 16:12 It is an abomination for kings to commit wickedness, For a throne is established on righteousness.
20Àá 16:13 Righteous lips are the delight of kings, And he who speaks right is loved.
20Àá 16:14 The wrath of a king is [as] messengers of death, But a wise man will appease it.
20Àá 16:15 In the light of a king's face is life, And his favor is like a cloud with the spring rain.
20Àá 16:16 How much better it is to get wisdom than gold! And to get understanding is to be chosen above silver.
20Àá 16:17 The highway of the upright is to depart from evil; He who watches his way preserves his life.
20Àá 16:18 Pride [goes] before destruction, And a haughty spirit before stumbling.
20Àá 16:19 It is better to be of a humble spirit with the lowly, Than to divide the spoil with the proud.
20Àá 16:20 He who gives attention to the word shall find good, And blessed is he who trusts in the LORD.
20Àá 16:21 The wise in heart will be called discerning, And sweetness of speech increases persuasiveness.
20Àá 16:22 Understanding is a fountain of life to him who has it, But the discipline of fools is folly.
20Àá 16:23 The heart of the wise teaches his mouth, And adds persuasiveness to his lips.
20Àá 16:24 Pleasant words are a honeycomb, Sweet to the soul and healing to the bones.
20Àá 16:25 There is a way [which seems] right to a man, But its end is the way of death.
20Àá 16:26 A worker's appetite works for him, For his hunger urges him [on.]
20Àá 16:27 A worthless man digs up evil, While his words are as a scorching fire.
20Àá 16:28 A perverse man spreads strife, And a slanderer separates intimate friends.
20Àá 16:29 A man of violence entices his neighbor, And leads him in a way that is not good.
20Àá 16:30 He who winks his eyes [does so] to devise perverse things; He who compresses his lips brings evil to pass.
20Àá 16:31 A gray head is a crown of glory; It is found in the way of righteousness.
20Àá 16:32 He who is slow to anger is better than the mighty, And he who rules his spirit, than he who captures a city.
20Àá 16:33 The lot is cast into the lap, But its every decision is from the LORD.
20Àá 17:1 Better is a dry morsel and quietness with it Than a house full of feasting with strife.
20Àá 17:2 A servant who acts wisely will rule over a son who acts shamefully, And will share in the inheritance among brothers.
20Àá 17:3 The refining pot is for silver and the furnace for gold, But the LORD tests hearts.
20Àá 17:4 An evildoer listens to wicked lips, A liar pays attention to a destructive tongue.
20Àá 17:5 He who mocks the poor reproaches his Maker; He who rejoices at calamity will not go unpunished.
20Àá 17:6 Grandchildren are the crown of old men, And the glory of sons is their fathers.
20Àá 17:7 Excellent speech is not fitting for a fool; Much less are lying lips to a prince.
20Àá 17:8 A bribe is a charm in the sight of its owner; Wherever he turns, he prospers.
20Àá 17:9 He who covers a transgression seeks love, But he who repeats a matter separates intimate friends.
20Àá 17:10 A rebuke goes deeper into one who has understanding Than a hundred blows into a fool.
20Àá 17:11 A rebellious man seeks only evil, So a cruel messenger will be sent against him.
20Àá 17:12 Let a man meet a bear robbed of her cubs, Rather than a fool in his folly.
20Àá 17:13 He who returns evil for good, Evil will not depart from his house.
20Àá 17:14 The beginning of strife is [like] letting out water, So abandon the quarrel before it breaks out.
20Àá 17:15 He who justifies the wicked, and he who condemns the righteous, Both of them alike are an abomination to the LORD.
20Àá 17:16 Why is there a price in the hand of a fool to buy wisdom, When he has no sense?
20Àá 17:17 A friend loves at all times, And a brother is born for adversity.
20Àá 17:18 A man lacking in sense pledges, And becomes surety in the presence of his neighbor.
20Àá 17:19 He who loves transgression loves strife; He who raises his door seeks destruction.
20Àá 17:20 He who has a crooked mind finds no good, And he who is perverted in his language falls into evil.
20Àá 17:21 He who begets a fool [does so] to his sorrow, And the father of a fool has no joy.
20Àá 17:22 A joyful heart is good medicine, But a broken spirit dries up the bones.
20Àá 17:23 A wicked man receives a bribe from the bosom To pervert the ways of justice.
20Àá 17:24 Wisdom is in the presence of the one who has understanding, But the eyes of a fool are on the ends of the earth.
20Àá 17:25 A foolish son is a grief to his father, And bitterness to her who bore him.
20Àá 17:26 It is also not good to fine the righteous, [Nor] to strike the noble for [their] uprightness.
20Àá 17:27 He who restrains his words has knowledge, And he who has a cool spirit is a man of understanding.
20Àá 17:28 Even a fool, when he keeps silent, is considered wise; When he closes his lips, he is [counted] prudent.
20Àá 18:1 He who separates himself seeks [his own] desire, He quarrels against all sound wisdom.
20Àá 18:2 A fool does not delight in understanding, But only in revealing his own mind.
20Àá 18:3 When a wicked man comes, contempt also comes, And with dishonor [comes] reproach.
20Àá 18:4 The words of a man's mouth are deep waters; The fountain of wisdom is a bubbling brook.
20Àá 18:5 To show partiality to the wicked is not good, [Nor] to thrust aside the righteous in judgment.
20Àá 18:6 A fool's lips bring strife, And his mouth calls for blows.
20Àá 18:7 A fool's mouth is his ruin, And his lips are the snare of his soul.
20Àá 18:8 The words of a whisperer are like dainty morsels, And they go down into the innermost parts of the body.
20Àá 18:9 He also who is slack in his work Is brother to him who destroys.
20Àá 18:10 The name of the LORD is a strong tower; The righteous runs into it and is safe.
20Àá 18:11 A rich man's wealth is his strong city, And like a high wall in his own imagination.
20Àá 18:12 Before destruction the heart of man is haughty, But humility [goes] before honor.
20Àá 18:13 He who gives an answer before he hears, It is folly and shame to him.
20Àá 18:14 The spirit of a man can endure his sickness, But a broken spirit who can bear?
20Àá 18:15 The mind of the prudent acquires knowledge, And the ear of the wise seeks knowledge.
20Àá 18:16 A man's gift makes room for him, And brings him before great men.
20Àá 18:17 The first to plead his case [seems] just, [Until] another comes and examines him.
20Àá 18:18 The lot puts an end to contentions, And decides between the mighty.
20Àá 18:19 A brother offended [is harder to be won] than a strong city, And contentions are like the bars of a castle.
20Àá 18:20 With the fruit of a man's mouth his stomach will be satisfied; He will be satisfied [with] the product of his lips.
20Àá 18:21 Death and life are in the power of the tongue, And those who love it will eat its fruit.
20Àá 18:22 He who finds a wife finds a good thing, And obtains favor from the LORD.
20Àá 18:23 The poor man utters supplications, But the rich man answers roughly.
20Àá 18:24 A man of [many] friends [comes] to ruin, But there is a friend who sticks closer than a brother.
20Àá 19:1 Better is a poor man who walks in his integrity Than he who is perverse in speech and is a fool.
20Àá 19:2 Also it is not good for a person to be without knowledge, And he who makes haste with his feet errs.
20Àá 19:3 The foolishness of man subverts his way, And his heart rages against the LORD.
20Àá 19:4 Wealth adds many friends, But a poor man is separated from his friend.
20Àá 19:5 A false witness will not go unpunished, And he who tells lies will not escape.
20Àá 19:6 Many will entreat the favor of a generous man, And every man is a friend to him who gives gifts.
20Àá 19:7 All the brothers of a poor man hate him; How much more do his friends go far from him! He pursues [them with] words, [but] they are gone.
20Àá 19:8 He who gets wisdom loves his own soul; He who keeps understanding will find good.
20Àá 19:9 A false witness will not go unpunished, And he who tells lies will perish.
20Àá 19:10 Luxury is not fitting for a fool; Much less for a slave to rule over princes.
20Àá 19:11 A man's discretion makes him slow to anger, And it is his glory to overlook a transgression.
20Àá 19:12 The king's wrath is like the roaring of a lion, But his favor is like dew on the grass.
20Àá 19:13 A foolish son is destruction to his father, And the contentions of a wife are a constant dripping.
20Àá 19:14 House and wealth are an inheritance from fathers, But a prudent wife is from the LORD.
20Àá 19:15 Laziness casts into a deep sleep, And an idle man will suffer hunger.
20Àá 19:16 He who keeps the commandment keeps his soul, [But] he who is careless of his ways will die.
20Àá 19:17 He who is gracious to a poor man lends to the LORD, And He will repay him for his good deed.
20Àá 19:18 Discipline your son while there is hope, And do not desire his death.
20Àá 19:19 [A man of] great anger shall bear the penalty, For if you rescue [ him,] you will only have to do it again.
20Àá 19:20 Listen to counsel and accept discipline, That you may be wise the rest of your days.
20Àá 19:21 Many are the plans in a man's heart, But the counsel of the LORD, it will stand.
20Àá 19:22 What is desirable in a man is his kindness, And [it is] better to be a poor man than a liar.
20Àá 19:23 The fear of the LORD [leads] to life, So that one may sleep satisfied, untouched by evil.
20Àá 19:24 The sluggard buries his hand in the dish, [And] will not even bring it back to his mouth.
20Àá 19:25 Strike a scoffer and the naive may become shrewd, But reprove one who has understanding and he will gain knowledge.
20Àá 19:26 He who assaults [his] father [and] drives [his] mother away Is a shameful and disgraceful son.
20Àá 19:27 Cease listening, my son, to discipline, [And you will] stray from the words of knowledge.
20Àá 19:28 A rascally witness makes a mockery of justice, And the mouth of the wicked spreads iniquity.
20Àá 19:29 Judgments are prepared for scoffers, And blows for the back of fools.
20Àá 20:1 Wine is a mocker, strong drink a brawler, And whoever is intoxicated by it is not wise.
20Àá 20:2 The terror of a king is like the growling of a lion; He who provokes him to anger forfeits his own life.
20Àá 20:3 Keeping away from strife is an honor for a man, But any fool will quarrel.
20Àá 20:4 The sluggard does not plow after the autumn, So he begs during the harvest and has nothing.
20Àá 20:5 A plan in the heart of a man is [like] deep water, But a man of understanding draws it out.
20Àá 20:6 Many a man proclaims his own loyalty, But who can find a trustworthy man?
20Àá 20:7 A righteous man who walks in his integrity-- How blessed are his sons after him.
20Àá 20:8 A king who sits on the throne of justice Disperses all evil with his eyes.
20Àá 20:9 Who can say, "I have cleansed my heart, I am pure from my sin"?
20Àá 20:10 Differing weights and differing measures, Both of them are abominable to the LORD.
20Àá 20:11 It is by his deeds that a lad distinguishes himself If his conduct is pure and right.
20Àá 20:12 The hearing ear and the seeing eye, The LORD has made both of them.
20Àá 20:13 Do not love sleep, lest you become poor; Open your eyes, [and] you will be satisfied with food.
20Àá 20:14 "Bad, bad," says the buyer; But when he goes his way, then he boasts.
20Àá 20:15 There is gold, and an abundance of jewels; But the lips of knowledge are a more precious thing.
20Àá 20:16 Take his garment when he becomes surety for a stranger; And for foreigners, hold him in pledge.
20Àá 20:17 Bread obtained by falsehood is sweet to a man, But afterward his mouth will be filled with gravel.
20Àá 20:18 Prepare plans by consultation, And make war by wise guidance.
20Àá 20:19 He who goes about as a slanderer reveals secrets, Therefore do not associate with a gossip.
20Àá 20:20 He who curses his father or his mother, His lamp will go out in time of darkness.
20Àá 20:21 An inheritance gained hurriedly at the beginning, Will not be blessed in the end.
20Àá 20:22 Do not say, "I will repay evil"; Wait for the LORD, and He will save you.
20Àá 20:23 Differing weights are an abomination to the LORD, And a false scale is not good.
20Àá 20:24 Man's steps are [ordained] by the LORD, How then can man understand his way?
20Àá 20:25 It is a snare for a man to say rashly, "It is holy!" And after the vows to make inquiry.
20Àá 20:26 A wise king winnows the wicked, And drives the [threshing] wheel over them.
20Àá 20:27 The spirit of man is the lamp of the LORD, Searching all the innermost parts of his being.
20Àá 20:28 Loyalty and truth preserve the king, And he upholds his throne by righteousness.
20Àá 20:29 The glory of young men is their strength, And the honor of old men is their gray hair.
20Àá 20:30 Stripes that wound scour away evil, And strokes [reach] the innermost parts.
20Àá 21:1 The king's heart is [like] channels of water in the hand of the LORD; He turns it wherever He wishes.
20Àá 21:2 Every man's way is right in his own eyes, But the LORD weighs the hearts.
20Àá 21:3 To do righteousness and justice Is desired by the LORD rather than sacrifice.
20Àá 21:4 Haughty eyes and a proud heart, The lamp of the wicked, is sin.
20Àá 21:5 The plans of the diligent [lead] surely to advantage, But everyone who is hasty [comes] surely to poverty.
20Àá 21:6 The getting of treasures by a lying tongue Is a fleeting vapor, the pursuit of death.
20Àá 21:7 The violence of the wicked will drag them away, Because they refuse to act with justice.
20Àá 21:8 The way of a guilty man is crooked, But as for the pure, his conduct is upright.
20Àá 21:9 It is better to live in a corner of a roof, Than in a house shared with a contentious woman.
20Àá 21:10 The soul of the wicked desires evil; His neighbor finds no favor in his eyes.
20Àá 21:11 When the scoffer is punished, the naive becomes wise; But when the wise is instructed, he receives knowledge.
20Àá 21:12 The righteous one considers the house of the wicked, Turning the wicked to ruin.
20Àá 21:13 He who shuts his ear to the cry of the poor Will also cry himself and not be answered.
20Àá 21:14 A gift in secret subdues anger, And a bribe in the bosom, strong wrath.
20Àá 21:15 The execution of justice is joy for the righteous, But is terror to the workers of iniquity.
20Àá 21:16 A man who wanders from the way of understanding Will rest in the assembly of the dead.
20Àá 21:17 He who loves pleasure [will become] a poor man; He who loves wine and oil will not become rich.
20Àá 21:18 The wicked is a ransom for the righteous, And the treacherous is in the place of the upright.
20Àá 21:19 It is better to live in a desert land, Than with a contentious and vexing woman.
20Àá 21:20 There is precious treasure and oil in the dwelling of the wise, But a foolish man swallows it up.
20Àá 21:21 He who pursues righteousness and loyalty Finds life, righteousness and honor.
20Àá 21:22 A wise man scales the city of the mighty, And brings down the stronghold in which they trust.
20Àá 21:23 He who guards his mouth and his tongue, Guards his soul from troubles.
20Àá 21:24 "Proud," "Haughty," "Scoffer," are his names, Who acts with insolent pride.
20Àá 21:25 The desire of the sluggard puts him to death, For his hands refuse to work;
20Àá 21:26 All day long he is craving, While the righteous gives and does not hold back.
20Àá 21:27 The sacrifice of the wicked is an abomination, How much more when he brings it with evil intent!
20Àá 21:28 A false witness will perish, But the man who listens [to the truth] will speak forever.
20Àá 21:29 A wicked man shows a bold face, But as for the upright, he makes his way sure.
20Àá 21:30 There is no wisdom and no understanding And no counsel against the LORD.
20Àá 21:31 The horse is prepared for the day of battle, But victory belongs to the LORD.
20Àá 22:1 A [good] name is to be more desired than great riches, Favor is better than silver and gold.
20Àá 22:2 The rich and the poor have a common bond, The LORD is the maker of them all.
20Àá 22:3 The prudent sees the evil and hides himself, But the naive go on, and are punished for it.
20Àá 22:4 The reward of humility [and] the fear of the LORD Are riches, honor and life.
20Àá 22:5 Thorns [and] snares are in the way of the perverse; He who guards himself will be far from them.
20Àá 22:6 Train up a child in the way he should go, Even when he is old he will not depart from it.
20Àá 22:7 The rich rules over the poor, And the borrower [becomes] the lender's slave.
20Àá 22:8 He who sows iniquity will reap vanity, And the rod of his fury will perish.
20Àá 22:9 He who is generous will be blessed, For he gives some of his food to the poor.
20Àá 22:10 Drive out the scoffer, and contention will go out, Even strife and dishonor will cease.
20Àá 22:11 He who loves purity of heart [And] whose speech is gracious, the king is his friend.
20Àá 22:12 The eyes of the LORD preserve knowledge, But He overthrows the words of the treacherous man.
20Àá 22:13 The sluggard says, "There is a lion outside; I shall be slain in the streets!"
20Àá 22:14 The mouth of an adulteress is a deep pit; He who is cursed of the LORD will fall into it.
20Àá 22:15 Foolishness is bound up in the heart of a child; The rod of discipline will remove it far from him.
20Àá 22:16 He who oppresses the poor to make much for himself Or who gives to the rich, [will] only [come to] poverty.
20Àá 22:17 Incline your ear and hear the words of the wise, And apply your mind to my knowledge;
20Àá 22:18 For it will be pleasant if you keep them within you, That they may be ready on your lips.
20Àá 22:19 So that your trust may be in the LORD, I have taught you today, even you.
20Àá 22:20 Have I not written to you excellent things Of counsels and knowledge,
20Àá 22:21 To make you know the certainty of the words of truth That you may correctly answer to him who sent you?
20Àá 22:22 Do not rob the poor because he is poor, Or crush the afflicted at the gate;
20Àá 22:23 For the LORD will plead their case, And take the life of those who rob them.
20Àá 22:24 Do not associate with a man [given] to anger; Or go with a hot-tempered man,
20Àá 22:25 Lest you learn his ways, And find a snare for yourself.
20Àá 22:26 Do not be among those who give pledges, Among those who become sureties for debts.
20Àá 22:27 If you have nothing with which to pay, Why should he take your bed from under you?
20Àá 22:28 Do not move the ancient boundary Which your fathers have set.
20Àá 22:29 Do you see a man skilled in his work? He will stand before kings; He will not stand before obscure men.
20Àá 23:1 When you sit down to dine with a ruler, Consider carefully what is before you;
20Àá 23:2 And put a knife to your throat, If you are a man of [great] appetite.
20Àá 23:3 Do not desire his delicacies, For it is deceptive food.
20Àá 23:4 Do not weary yourself to gain wealth, Cease from your consideration [of it.]
20Àá 23:5 When you set your eyes on it, it is gone. For [wealth] certainly makes itself wings, Like an eagle that flies [toward] the heavens.
20Àá 23:6 Do not eat the bread of a selfish man, Or desire his delicacies;
20Àá 23:7 For as he thinks within himself, so he is. He says to you, "Eat and drink!" But his heart is not with you.
20Àá 23:8 You will vomit up the morsel you have eaten, And waste your compliments.
20Àá 23:9 Do not speak in the hearing of a fool, For he will despise the wisdom of your words.
20Àá 23:10 Do not move the ancient boundary, Or go into the fields of the fatherless;
20Àá 23:11 For their Redeemer is strong; He will plead their case against you.
20Àá 23:12 Apply your heart to discipline, And your ears to words of knowledge.
20Àá 23:13 Do not hold back discipline from the child, Although you beat him with the rod, he will not die.
20Àá 23:14 You shall beat him with the rod, And deliver his soul from Sheol.
20Àá 23:15 My son, if your heart is wise, My own heart also will be glad;
20Àá 23:16 And my inmost being will rejoice, When your lips speak what is right.
20Àá 23:17 Do not let your heart envy sinners, But [live] in the fear of the LORD always.
20Àá 23:18 Surely there is a future, And your hope will not be cut off.
20Àá 23:19 Listen, my son, and be wise, And direct your heart in the way.
20Àá 23:20 Do not be with heavy drinkers of wine, [Or] with gluttonous eaters of meat;
20Àá 23:21 For the heavy drinker and the glutton will come to poverty, And drowsiness will clothe [a man] with rags.
20Àá 23:22 Listen to your father who begot you, And do not despise your mother when she is old.
20Àá 23:23 Buy truth, and do not sell [it,] [Get] wisdom and instruction and understanding.
20Àá 23:24 The father of the righteous will greatly rejoice, And he who begets a wise son will be glad in him.
20Àá 23:25 Let your father and your mother be glad, And let her rejoice who gave birth to you.
20Àá 23:26 Give me your heart, my son, And let your eyes delight in my ways.
20Àá 23:27 For a harlot is a deep pit, And an adulterous woman is a narrow well.
20Àá 23:28 Surely she lurks as a robber, And increases the faithless among men.
20Àá 23:29 Who has woe? Who has sorrow? Who has contentions? Who has complaining? Who has wounds without cause? Who has redness of eyes?
20Àá 23:30 Those who linger long over wine, Those who go to taste mixed wine.
20Àá 23:31 Do not look on the wine when it is red, When it sparkles in the cup, When it goes down smoothly;
20Àá 23:32 At the last it bites like a serpent, And stings like a viper.
20Àá 23:33 Your eyes will see strange things, And your mind will utter perverse things.
20Àá 23:34 And you will be like one who lies down in the middle of the sea, Or like one who lies down on the top of a mast.
20Àá 23:35 "They struck me, [but] I did not become ill; They beat me, [but] I did not know [it.] When shall I awake? I will seek another drink."
20Àá 24:1 Do not be envious of evil men, Nor desire to be with them;
20Àá 24:2 For their minds devise violence, And their lips talk of trouble.
20Àá 24:3 By wisdom a house is built, And by understanding it is established;
20Àá 24:4 And by knowledge the rooms are filled With all precious and pleasant riches.
20Àá 24:5 A wise man is strong, And a man of knowledge increases power.
20Àá 24:6 For by wise guidance you will wage war, And in abundance of counselors there is victory.
20Àá 24:7 Wisdom is too high for a fool, He does not open his mouth in the gate.
20Àá 24:8 He who plans to do evil, Men will call him a schemer.
20Àá 24:9 The devising of folly is sin, And the scoffer is an abomination to men.
20Àá 24:10 If you are slack in the day of distress, Your strength is limited.
20Àá 24:11 Deliver those who are being taken away to death, And those who are staggering to slaughter, O hold [them] back.
20Àá 24:12 If you say, "See, we did not know this," Does He not consider [it] who weighs the hearts? And does He not know [it] who keeps your soul? And will He not render to man according to his work?
20Àá 24:13 My son, eat honey, for it is good, Yes, the honey from the comb is sweet to your taste;
20Àá 24:14 Know [that] wisdom is thus for your soul; If you find [it,] then there will be a future, And your hope will not be cut off.
20Àá 24:15 Do not lie in wait, O wicked man, against the dwelling of the righteous; Do not destroy his resting place;
20Àá 24:16 For a righteous man falls seven times, and rises again, But the wicked stumble in [time of] calamity.
20Àá 24:17 Do not rejoice when your enemy falls, And do not let your heart be glad when he stumbles;
20Àá 24:18 Lest the LORD see [it] and be displeased, And He turn away His anger from him.
20Àá 24:19 Do not fret because of evildoers, Or be envious of the wicked;
20Àá 24:20 For there will be no future for the evil man; The lamp of the wicked will be put out.
20Àá 24:21 My son, fear the LORD and the king; Do not associate with those who are given to change;
20Àá 24:22 For their calamity will rise suddenly, And who knows the ruin [that comes] from both of them?
20Àá 24:23 These also are sayings of the wise. To show partiality in judgment is not good.
20Àá 24:24 He who says to the wicked, "You are righteous," Peoples will curse him, nations will abhor him;
20Àá 24:25 But to those who rebuke the [wicked] will be delight, And a good blessing will come upon them.
20Àá 24:26 He kisses the lips Who gives a right answer.
20Àá 24:27 Prepare your work outside, And make it ready for yourself in the field; Afterwards, then, build your house.
20Àá 24:28 Do not be a witness against your neighbor without cause, And do not deceive with your lips.
20Àá 24:29 Do not say, "Thus I shall do to him as he has done to me; I will render to the man according to his work."
20Àá 24:30 I passed by the field of the sluggard, And by the vineyard of the man lacking sense;
20Àá 24:31 And behold, it was completely overgrown with thistles, Its surface was covered with nettles, And its stone wall was broken down.
20Àá 24:32 When I saw, I reflected upon it; I looked, [and] received instruction.
20Àá 24:33 "A little sleep, a little slumber, A little folding of the hands to rest,"
20Àá 24:34 Then your poverty will come [as] a robber, And your want like an armed man.
20Àá 25:1 These also are proverbs of Solomon which the men of Hezekiah, king of Judah, transcribed.
20Àá 25:2 It is the glory of God to conceal a matter, But the glory of kings is to search out a matter.
20Àá 25:3 [As] the heavens for height and the earth for depth, So the heart of kings is unsearchable.
20Àá 25:4 Take away the dross from the silver, And there comes out a vessel for the smith;
20Àá 25:5 Take away the wicked [from] before the king, And his throne will be established in righteousness.
20Àá 25:6 Do not claim honor in the presence of the king, And do not stand in the place of great men;
20Àá 25:7 For it is better that it be said to you, "Come up here," Than that you should be put lower in the presence of the prince, Whom your eyes have seen.
20Àá 25:8 Do not go out hastily to argue [your case;] Otherwise, what will you do in the end, When your neighbor puts you to shame?
20Àá 25:9 Argue your case with your neighbor, And do not reveal the secret of another,
20Àá 25:10 Lest he who hears [it] reproach you, And the evil report about you not pass away.
20Àá 25:11 [Like] apples of gold in settings of silver Is a word spoken in right circumstances.
20Àá 25:12 [Like] an earring of gold and an ornament of fine gold Is a wise reprover to a listening ear.
20Àá 25:13 Like the cold of snow in the time of harvest Is a faithful messenger to those who send him, For he refreshes the soul of his masters.
20Àá 25:14 [Like] clouds and wind without rain Is a man who boasts of his gifts falsely.
20Àá 25:15 By forbearance a ruler may be persuaded, And a soft tongue breaks the bone.
20Àá 25:16 Have you found honey? Eat [only] what you need, Lest you have it in excess and vomit it.
20Àá 25:17 Let your foot rarely be in your neighbor's house, Lest he become weary of you and hate you.
20Àá 25:18 [Like] a club and a sword and a sharp arrow Is a man who bears false witness against his neighbor.
20Àá 25:19 [Like] a bad tooth and an unsteady foot Is confidence in a faithless man in time of trouble.
20Àá 25:20 [Like] one who takes off a garment on a cold day, [or like] vinegar on soda, Is he who sings songs to a troubled heart.
20Àá 25:21 If your enemy is hungry, give him food to eat; And if he is thirsty, give him water to drink;
20Àá 25:22 For you will heap burning coals on his head, And the LORD will reward you.
20Àá 25:23 The north wind brings forth rain, And a backbiting tongue, an angry countenance.
20Àá 25:24 It is better to live in a corner of the roof Than in a house shared with a contentious woman.
20Àá 25:25 [Like] cold water to a weary soul, So is good news from a distant land.
20Àá 25:26 [Like] a trampled spring and a polluted well Is a righteous man who gives way before the wicked.
20Àá 25:27 It is not good to eat much honey, Nor is it glory to search out one's own glory.
20Àá 25:28 [Like] a city that is broken into [and] without walls Is a man who has no control over his spirit.
20Àá 26:1 Like snow in summer and like rain in harvest, So honor is not fitting for a fool.
20Àá 26:2 Like a sparrow in [its] flitting, like a swallow in [its] flying, So a curse without cause does not alight.
20Àá 26:3 A whip is for the horse, a bridle for the donkey, And a rod for the back of fools.
20Àá 26:4 Do not answer a fool according to his folly, Lest you also be like him.
20Àá 26:5 Answer a fool as his folly [deserves], Lest he be wise in his own eyes.
20Àá 26:6 He cuts off [his own] feet, [and] drinks violence Who sends a message by the hand of a fool.
20Àá 26:7 [Like] the legs [which] hang down from the lame, So is a proverb in the mouth of fools.
20Àá 26:8 Like one who binds a stone in a sling, So is he who gives honor to a fool.
20Àá 26:9 [Like] a thorn [which] falls into the hand of a drunkard, So is a proverb in the mouth of fools.
20Àá 26:10 [Like] an archer who wounds everyone, So is he who hires a fool or who hires those who pass by.
20Àá 26:11 Like a dog that returns to its vomit Is a fool who repeats his folly.
20Àá 26:12 Do you see a man wise in his own eyes? There is more hope for a fool than for him.
20Àá 26:13 The sluggard says, "There is a lion in the road! A lion is in the open square!"
20Àá 26:14 [As] the door turns on its hinges, So [does] the sluggard on his bed.
20Àá 26:15 The sluggard buries his hand in the dish; He is weary of bringing it to his mouth again.
20Àá 26:16 The sluggard is wiser in his own eyes Than seven men who can give a discreet answer.
20Àá 26:17 [Like] one who takes a dog by the ears Is he who passes by [and] meddles with strife not belonging to him.
20Àá 26:18 Like a madman who throws Firebrands, arrows and death,
20Àá 26:19 So is the man who deceives his neighbor, And says, "Was I not joking?"
20Àá 26:20 For lack of wood the fire goes out, And where there is no whisperer, contention quiets down.
20Àá 26:21 [Like] charcoal to hot embers and wood to fire, So is a contentious man to kindle strife.
20Àá 26:22 The words of a whisperer are like dainty morsels, And they go down into the innermost parts of the body.
20Àá 26:23 [Like] an earthen vessel overlaid with silver dross Are burning lips and a wicked heart.
20Àá 26:24 He who hates disguises [it] with his lips, But he lays up deceit in his heart.
20Àá 26:25 When he speaks graciously, do not believe him, For there are seven abominations in his heart.
20Àá 26:26 [Though his] hatred covers itself with guile, His wickedness will be revealed before the assembly.
20Àá 26:27 He who digs a pit will fall into it, And he who rolls a stone, it will come back on him.
20Àá 26:28 A lying tongue hates those it crushes, And a flattering mouth works ruin.
20Àá 27:1 Do not boast about tomorrow, For you do not know what a day may bring forth.
20Àá 27:2 Let another praise you, and not your own mouth; A stranger, and not your own lips.
20Àá 27:3 A stone is heavy and the sand weighty, But the provocation of a fool is heavier than both of them.
20Àá 27:4 Wrath is fierce and anger is a flood, But who can stand before jealousy?
20Àá 27:5 Better is open rebuke Than love that is concealed.
20Àá 27:6 Faithful are the wounds of a friend, But deceitful are the kisses of an enemy.
20Àá 27:7 A sated man loathes honey, But to a famished man any bitter thing is sweet.
20Àá 27:8 Like a bird that wanders from her nest, So is a man who wanders from his home.
20Àá 27:9 Oil and perfume make the heart glad, So a man's counsel is sweet to his friend.
20Àá 27:10 Do not forsake your own friend or your father's friend, And do not go to your brother's house in the day of your calamity; Better is a neighbor who is near than a brother far away.
20Àá 27:11 Be wise, my son, and make my heart glad, That I may reply to him who reproaches me.
20Àá 27:12 A prudent man sees evil [and] hides himself, The naive proceed [and] pay the penalty.
20Àá 27:13 Take his garment when he becomes surety for a stranger; And for an adulterous woman hold him in pledge.
20Àá 27:14 He who blesses his friend with a loud voice early in the morning, It will be reckoned a curse to him.
20Àá 27:15 A constant dripping on a day of steady rain And a contentious woman are alike;
20Àá 27:16 He who would restrain her restrains the wind, And grasps oil with his right hand.
20Àá 27:17 Iron sharpens iron, So one man sharpens another.
20Àá 27:18 He who tends the fig tree will eat its fruit; And he who cares for his master will be honored.
20Àá 27:19 As in water face [reflects] face, So the heart of man [reflects] man.
20Àá 27:20 Sheol and Abaddon are never satisfied, Nor are the eyes of man ever satisfied.
20Àá 27:21 The crucible is for silver and the furnace for gold, And a man [is tested] by the praise accorded him.
20Àá 27:22 Though you pound a fool in a mortar with a pestle along with crushed grain, [Yet] his folly will not depart from him.
20Àá 27:23 Know well the condition of your flocks, [And] pay attention to your herds;
20Àá 27:24 For riches are not forever, Nor does a crown [endure] to all generations.
20Àá 27:25 [When] the grass disappears, the new growth is seen, And the herbs of the mountains are gathered in,
20Àá 27:26 The lambs [will be] for your clothing, And the goats [will bring] the price of a field,
20Àá 27:27 And [there will be] goats' milk enough for your food, For the food of your household, And sustenance for your maidens.
20Àá 28:1 The wicked flee when no one is pursuing, But the righteous are bold as a lion.
20Àá 28:2 By the transgression of a land many are its princes, But by a man of understanding [and] knowledge, so it endures.
20Àá 28:3 A poor man who oppresses the lowly Is [like] a driving rain which leaves no food.
20Àá 28:4 Those who forsake the law praise the wicked, But those who keep the law strive with them.
20Àá 28:5 Evil men do not understand justice, But those who seek the LORD understand all things.
20Àá 28:6 Better is the poor who walks in his integrity, Than he who is crooked though he be rich.
20Àá 28:7 He who keeps the law is a discerning son, But he who is a companion of gluttons humiliates his father.
20Àá 28:8 He who increases his wealth by interest and usury, Gathers it for him who is gracious to the poor.
20Àá 28:9 He who turns away his ear from listening to the law, Even his prayer is an abomination.
20Àá 28:10 He who leads the upright astray in an evil way Will himself fall into his own pit, But the blameless will inherit good.
20Àá 28:11 The rich man is wise in his own eyes, But the poor who has understanding sees through him.
20Àá 28:12 When the righteous triumph, there is great glory, But when the wicked rise, men hide themselves.
20Àá 28:13 He who conceals his transgressions will not prosper, But he who confesses and forsakes [them] will find compassion.
20Àá 28:14 How blessed is the man who fears always, But he who hardens his heart will fall into calamity.
20Àá 28:15 [Like] a roaring lion and a rushing bear Is a wicked ruler over a poor people.
20Àá 28:16 A leader who is a great oppressor lacks understanding, [But] he who hates unjust gain will prolong [his] days.
20Àá 28:17 A man who is laden with the guilt of human blood Will be a fugitive until death; let no one support him.
20Àá 28:18 He who walks blamelessly will be delivered, But he who is crooked will fall all at once.
20Àá 28:19 He who tills his land will have plenty of food, But he who follows empty [pursuits] will have poverty in plenty.
20Àá 28:20 A faithful man will abound with blessings, But he who makes haste to be rich will not go unpunished.
20Àá 28:21 To show partiality is not good, Because for a piece of bread a man will transgress.
20Àá 28:22 A man with an evil eye hastens after wealth, And does not know that want will come upon him.
20Àá 28:23 He who rebukes a man will afterward find [more] favor Than he who flatters with the tongue.
20Àá 28:24 He who robs his father or his mother, And says, "It is not a transgression," Is the companion of a man who destroys.
20Àá 28:25 An arrogant man stirs up strife, But he who trusts in the LORD will prosper.
20Àá 28:26 He who trusts in his own heart is a fool, But he who walks wisely will be delivered.
20Àá 28:27 He who gives to the poor will never want, But he who shuts his eyes will have many curses.
20Àá 28:28 When the wicked rise, men hide themselves; But when they perish, the righteous increase.
20Àá 29:1 A man who hardens [his] neck after much reproof Will suddenly be broken beyond remedy.
20Àá 29:2 When the righteous increase, the people rejoice, But when a wicked man rules, people groan.
20Àá 29:3 A man who loves wisdom makes his father glad, But he who keeps company with harlots wastes [his] wealth.
20Àá 29:4 The king gives stability to the land by justice, But a man who takes bribes overthrows it.
20Àá 29:5 A man who flatters his neighbor Is spreading a net for his steps.
20Àá 29:6 By transgression an evil man is ensnared, But the righteous sings and rejoices.
20Àá 29:7 The righteous is concerned for the rights of the poor, The wicked does not understand [such] concern.
20Àá 29:8 Scorners set a city aflame, But wise men turn away anger.
20Àá 29:9 When a wise man has a controversy with a foolish man, The foolish man either rages or laughs, and there is no rest.
20Àá 29:10 Men of bloodshed hate the blameless, But the upright are concerned for his life.
20Àá 29:11 A fool always loses his temper, But a wise man holds it back.
20Àá 29:12 If a ruler pays attention to falsehood, All his ministers [become] wicked.
20Àá 29:13 The poor man and the oppressor have this in common£º The LORD gives light to the eyes of both.
20Àá 29:14 If a king judges the poor with truth, His throne will be established forever.
20Àá 29:15 The rod and reproof give wisdom, But a child who gets his own way brings shame to his mother.
20Àá 29:16 When the wicked increase, transgression increases; But the righteous will see their fall.
20Àá 29:17 Correct your son, and he will give you comfort; He will also delight your soul.
20Àá 29:18 Where there is no vision, the people are unrestrained, But happy is he who keeps the law.
20Àá 29:19 A slave will not be instructed by words [alone;] For though he understands, there will be no response.
20Àá 29:20 Do you see a man who is hasty in his words? There is more hope for a fool than for him.
20Àá 29:21 He who pampers his slave from childhood Will in the end find him to be a son.
20Àá 29:22 An angry man stirs up strife, And a hot-tempered man abounds in transgression.
20Àá 29:23 A man's pride will bring him low, But a humble spirit will obtain honor.
20Àá 29:24 He who is a partner with a thief hates his own life; He hears the oath but tells nothing.
20Àá 29:25 The fear of man brings a snare, But he who trusts in the LORD will be exalted.
20Àá 29:26 Many seek the ruler's favor, But justice for man [comes] from the LORD.
20Àá 29:27 An unjust man is abominable to the righteous, And he who is upright in the way is abominable to the wicked.
20Àá 30:1 The words of Agur the son of Jakeh, the oracle. The man declares to Ithiel, to Ithiel and Ucal£º
20Àá 30:2 Surely I am more stupid than any man, And I do not have the understanding of a man.
20Àá 30:3 Neither have I learned wisdom, Nor do I have the knowledge of the Holy One.
20Àá 30:4 Who has ascended into heaven and descended? Who has gathered the wind in His fists? Who has wrapped the waters in His garment? Who has established all the ends of the earth? What is His name or His son's name? Surely you know!
20Àá 30:5 Every word of God is tested; He is a shield to those who take refuge in Him.
20Àá 30:6 Do not add to His words Lest He reprove you, and you be proved a liar.
20Àá 30:7 Two things I asked of Thee, Do not refuse me before I die£º
20Àá 30:8 Keep deception and lies far from me, Give me neither poverty nor riches; Feed me with the food that is my portion,
20Àá 30:9 Lest I be full and deny [Thee] and say, "Who is the LORD?" Or lest I be in want and steal, And profane the name of my God.
20Àá 30:10 Do not slander a slave to his master, Lest he curse you and you be found guilty.
20Àá 30:11 There is a kind of [man] who curses his father, And does not bless his mother.
20Àá 30:12 There is a kind who is pure in his own eyes, Yet is not washed from his filthiness.
20Àá 30:13 There is a kind-- oh how lofty are his eyes! And his eyelids are raised [in arrogance.]
20Àá 30:14 There is a kind of [man] whose teeth are [like] swords, And his jaw teeth [like] knives, To devour the afflicted from the earth, And the needy from among men.
20Àá 30:15 The leech has two daughters, "Give," "Give." There are three things that will not be satisfied, Four that will not say, "Enough"£º
20Àá 30:16 Sheol, and the barren womb, Earth that is never satisfied with water, And fire that never says, "Enough."
20Àá 30:17 The eye that mocks a father, And scorns a mother, The ravens of the valley will pick it out, And the young eagles will eat it.
20Àá 30:18 There are three things which are too wonderful for me, Four which I do not understand£º
20Àá 30:19 The way of an eagle in the sky, The way of a serpent on a rock, The way of a ship in the middle of the sea, And the way of a man with a maid.
20Àá 30:20 This is the way of an adulterous woman£º She eats and wipes her mouth, And says, "I have done no wrong."
20Àá 30:21 Under three things the earth quakes, And under four, it cannot bear up£º
20Àá 30:22 Under a slave when he becomes king, And a fool when he is satisfied with food,
20Àá 30:23 Under an unloved woman when she gets a husband, And a maidservant when she supplants her mistress.
20Àá 30:24 Four things are small on the earth, But they are exceedingly wise£º
20Àá 30:25 The ants are not a strong folk, But they prepare their food in the summer;
20Àá 30:26 The badgers are not mighty folk, Yet they make their houses in the rocks;
20Àá 30:27 The locusts have no king, Yet all of them go out in ranks;
20Àá 30:28 The lizard you may grasp with the hands, Yet it is in kings' palaces.
20Àá 30:29 There are three things which are stately in [their] march, Even four which are stately when they walk£º
20Àá 30:30 The lion [which] is mighty among beasts And does not retreat before any,
20Àá 30:31 The strutting cock, the male goat also, And a king [when his] army is with him.
20Àá 30:32 If you have been foolish in exalting yourself Or if you have plotted [evil, put your] hand on your mouth.
20Àá 30:33 For the churning of milk produces butter, And pressing the nose brings forth blood; So the churning of anger produces strife.
20Àá 31:1 The words of King Lemuel, the oracle which his mother taught him.
20Àá 31:2 What, O my son? And what, O son of my womb? And what, O son of my vows?
20Àá 31:3 Do not give your strength to women, Or your ways to that which destroys kings.
20Àá 31:4 It is not for kings, O Lemuel, It is not for kings to drink wine, Or for rulers to desire strong drink,
20Àá 31:5 Lest they drink and forget what is decreed, And pervert the rights of all the afflicted.
20Àá 31:6 Give strong drink to him who is perishing, And wine to him whose life is bitter.
20Àá 31:7 Let him drink and forget his poverty, And remember his trouble no more.
20Àá 31:8 Open your mouth for the dumb, For the rights of all the unfortunate.
20Àá 31:9 Open your mouth, judge righteously, And defend the rights of the afflicted and needy.
20Àá 31:10 An excellent wife, who can find? For her worth is far above jewels.
20Àá 31:11 The heart of her husband trusts in her, And he will have no lack of gain.
20Àá 31:12 She does him good and not evil All the days of her life.
20Àá 31:13 She looks for wool and flax, And works with her hands in delight.
20Àá 31:14 She is like merchant ships; She brings her food from afar.
20Àá 31:15 She rises also while it is still night, And gives food to her household, And portions to her maidens.
20Àá 31:16 She considers a field and buys it; From her earnings she plants a vineyard.
20Àá 31:17 She girds herself with strength, And makes her arms strong.
20Àá 31:18 She senses that her gain is good; Her lamp does not go out at night.
20Àá 31:19 She stretches out her hands to the distaff, And her hands grasp the spindle.
20Àá 31:20 She extends her hand to the poor; And she stretches out her hands to the needy.
20Àá 31:21 She is not afraid of the snow for her household, For all her household are clothed with scarlet.
20Àá 31:22 She makes coverings for herself; Her clothing is fine linen and purple.
20Àá 31:23 Her husband is known in the gates, When he sits among the elders of the land.
20Àá 31:24 She makes linen garments and sells [them,] And supplies belts to the tradesmen.
20Àá 31:25 Strength and dignity are her clothing, And she smiles at the future.
20Àá 31:26 She opens her mouth in wisdom, And the teaching of kindness is on her tongue.
20Àá 31:27 She looks well to the ways of her household, And does not eat the bread of idleness.
20Àá 31:28 Her children rise up and bless her; Her husband [also,] and he praises her, [saying:]
20Àá 31:29 "Many daughters have done nobly, But you excel them all."
20Àá 31:30 Charm is deceitful and beauty is vain, [But] a woman who fears the LORD, she shall be praised.
20Àá 31:31 Give her the product of her hands, And let her works praise her in the gates.
